] (1880\u20131962)\n*[[Lionel Monckton]] \u2013 composer of [[Edwardian musical comedies]]\n*[[Hugh Montgomery (Royal Marines officer)|Lieutenant-Colonel Hugh Montgomery]] \u2013 [[Royal Marines]] and intelligence officer, one of the IRA-assassinated [[Cairo Gang]]\n*[[Henrietta Moraes]] \u2013 writer, artist's model and muse to [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]]\n*[[Roderick Murchison]] \u2013 geologist, originator of the [[Silurian]] system\n*[[Adelaide Neilson]] \u2013 actress\n*[[William Gustavus Nicholson, 1st Baron Nicholson]] \u2013 first [[Chief of the Imperial General Staff]]\n*Count [[Stanis\u0142aw Julian Ostror\u00f3g]] \u2013 [[Crimean War]] veteran, photographer\n*[[Eug\u00e8ne Oudin]] \u2013 American baritone\n*[[Sydney, Lady Morgan|Sydney Owenson, Lady Morgan]] \u2013 Anglo-Irish writer\n*[[William Palliser|Sir William Palliser]] \u2013 inventor and builder of [[Barons Court tube station|Barons Court]]\n*[[Emmeline Pankhurst]] \u2013 leading [[suffragette]]\n*Private [[Samuel Parkes (VC)|Samuel Parkes]] \u2013 [[Victoria Cross|VC]] recipient\n*[[Mrs Howard Paul]] \u2013 actress and singer\n*[[Charles Henry Pearson]] and his brother [[John Pearson (judge)|Sir John Pearson]]\n*[[Sir John Lysaght Pennefather]] \u2013 general\n*[[Henry Pettitt]] \u2013 actor, a noteworthy monument with a sculpted head of Pettitt\n*[[John Birnie Philip]] - sculptor and father in law of the artist [[James Whistler]]\n*[[Percy Sinclair Pilcher]] \u2013 inventor and pioneering aviator\n*[[Valentine Cameron Prinsep]] \u2013 [[Pre-Raphaelite]] painter\n*Sir [[Robert Rawlinson]] \u2013 military officer\n*[[William Henry Macleod Read]] \u2013 political and social activist and merchant\n*[[Fanny Ronalds]] \u2013 American socialite and singer\n*[[William Michael Rooke]] \u2013 Irish composer\n*[[Blanche Roosevelt]] \u2013 American opera singer and author\n*[[Tim Rose]] \u2013 American singer-songwriter\n*[[Alexander Rotinoff]] \u2013 architect\n*[[William Howard Russell]] \u2013 journalist and war correspondent\n*Sir [[Doyle Money Shaw]] \u2013 naval officer\n*[[William Siborne]] \u2013 Army officer and military historian, maker of the [[Siborne model]]\n*[[Samuel Smiles]] \u2013 biographer and inventor of \"self-help\"\n*[[Albert Richard Smith]] \u2013 writer\n*[[John Snow]] \u2013 anaesthetist and epidemiologist, who demonstrated the link between cholera and infected water\n*[[Farren Soutar]] \u2013 musical comedy actor\n*[[Lord Alan Spencer-Churchill]] - officer [[8th Hussars]]\n*[[Augustus Spencer|General The Hon. Sir Augustus Almeric Spencer GCB]] - officer\n*[[Charles Stent]] - dentist after whom the medical [[Stent]] is named\n*[[H.F. Stephens]] \u2013 light railway pioneer\n*[[Robert Story (poet)|Robert Story]] \u2013 poet\n*[[Fred Sullivan]], Thomas Sullivan and Mary Clementina Sullivan \u2013 brother, father and mother of [[Arthur Sullivan]], composer\n*[[Jerzy Swirski]] \u2013 vice-admiral and head of the Polish navy, 1925\u20131947 \n*[[Richard Tauber]] \u2013 operatic tenor\n*[[Sir David Tennant]] \u2013 Speaker of the Cape Parliament.\n*[[William Terriss]] - actor\n*[[Ernest Thesiger]] \u2013 character actor, ''[[The Old Dark House (1932 film)|The Old Dark House]]'' and ''[[Bride of Frankenstein]]''\n*[[Frederic Thesiger, 1st Baron Chelmsford]] \u2013 jurist and statesman\n*[[Frederic Augustus Thesiger, 2nd Baron Chelmsford]] \u2013 Commander-in-Chief in the [[Zulu War]]\n*[[John Evan Thomas]] \u2013 sculptor\n*[[Brandon Thomas]] \u2013 author of [[Charley's Aunt]]\n*[[Stefan Tyszkiewicz]] \u2013 engineer, inventor, car manufacturer, political activist\n*[[Charles Blacker Vignoles]] \u2013 railway engineer, and inventor of the [[Vignoles rail]]\n*[[Fred Vokes]] - actor and dancer\n*[[Jessie Vokes]] - actress and dancer\n*[[Victoria Vokes]] - actress\n*Colonel [[Richard Wadeson]] \u2013 [[Victoria Cross|VC]] recipient\n*[[Edward Wadsworth]] \u2013 artist\n*[[Thomas Attwood Walmisley]] \u2013 composer and [[organ (music)|organist]].\n*[[Robert Warburton|Sir Robert Warburton]] \u2013 Anglo-Indian soldier and administrator\n*[[Jane Wardle]] - clinical psychologist and pioneer of cancer prevention\n*Flight Sub Lieutenant [[Reginald Alexander John Warneford]] \u2013 [[Victoria Cross|VC]] recipient\n*[[Philip Watts (naval architect)|Sir Philip Watts]] \u2013 naval architect, designer of the Elswick cruiser and HMS ''Dreadnought''\n*[[Andrew Scott Waugh|Sir Andrew Scott Waugh]] \u2013 army officer and surveyor, who named the highest mountain in the world after Sir [[George Everest]]\n*[[Benjamin Nottingham Webster]] \u2013 actor, theatre manager and playwright\n*[[Thomas Spencer Wells|Sir Thomas Spencer Wells]] \u2013 surgeon to [[Queen Victoria]], medical professor and president of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of England]]\n*Private [[Francis Wheatley (soldier)|Francis Wheatley]] \u2013 [[Victoria Cross|VC]] recipient\n*[[Jack Whitley]] \u2013 professional footballer\n*[[William Fenwick Williams|Sir William Fenwick Williams]] \u2013 general, pasha and governor\n*[[John Wisden]] \u2013 cricketer and founder of ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]''\n*[[Bennet Woodcroft]] \u2013 textile manufacturer, industrial archaeologist, pioneer of marine propulsion, [[patent]] reformer and first clerk to the Patent Commissioners\n*[[Thomas Wright (antiquarian)|Thomas Wright]] \u2013 [[antiquarian]] and writer\n*[[Johannes Zukertort]] aka Jan Hermann Zukertort \u2013 Polish-Jewish chess master\n\nIt was originally planned that Sir Arthur Sullivan of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] fame would also be buried there with his family, until [[Queen Victoria]] insisted on his interment in [[St Paul's Cathedral]].\n\n===Exhumations===\nIn the late 1880s when the nearby [[Earls Court Exhibition Centre|Earl's Court Exhibition Grounds]] played host to the American Show with [[Buffalo Bill]], a number of [[First Nations]] American performers in the show, died while on tour in Britain. The Sioux chief, Long Wolf, a veteran of the [[Oglala Lakota|Oglala Sioux]] wars was buried here on 13 June 1892 having died age 59 of bronchial pneumonia. He shared the grave with a 17-month-old Sioux girl named White Star believed to have fallen from her mother's arms while on horseback. 105 years later a British woman named Elizabeth Knight traced his family and campaigned with them to have his remains returned to the land of his birth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1997/09/26/chief-long-wolfs-last-journey/48cd6840-f6fa-4b47-8e03-0c31d419608b/|title=Chief Long Wolf's Last Journey|last=Balz|first=Dan|date=26 September 1997|work=Washington Post|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In 1997, Chief Long Wolf was finally moved to a new plot in the Wolf Creek Cemetery (ancestral burial ground of the Oglala Sioux tribe) at [[Pine Ridge, South Dakota]].\nHis great grandson John Black Feather said \"Back then, they had burials at sea, they did ask his wife if she wanted to take him home and she figured that as soon as they hit the water they would throw him overboard, so that's why they left him here.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/london/content/articles/2005/05/10/brompton_cemetery_feature.shtml |title=Brompton Cemetery |publisher=BBC |date=9 April 2008 |accessdate=1 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://cgi.cnn.com/WORLD/9709/25/chief.long.wolf/ |title=Chief Long Wolf goes home, 105 years late |publisher=CNN |date=25 September 1997 |accessdate=1 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419032411/http://cgi.cnn.com/WORLD/9709/25/chief.long.wolf/ |archivedate=19 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |archivedate=26 September 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050926210653/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F1997%2F05%2F05%2Fnwol05.html |title=Sioux reclaim tribal chief from English grave |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=1 March 2010 |date=5 May 1997 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/1997/05/05/nwol05.html |last=Weaver |first=Maurice |location=London |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere was a [[Brul\u00e9|Brul\u00e9 Sioux]] tribesman buried in Brompton named [[Paul Eagle Star]]. His plot was in the same section as Oglala Sioux warrior Surrounded By the Enemy who died in 1887 from a lung infection at age 22.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/sioux-mystery-solved-640339|title=Sioux mystery solved|last=|first=|date=3 October 2007|work=Manchester Evening News|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref> Like Long Wolf, he took part of Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show. Paul died a few days after breaking his ankle when he fell off a horse in August 1891. His casket was exhumed in spring of 1999 by his grandchildren, Moses and Lucy Eagle Star. The reburial took place in [[Rosebud, South Dakota|Rosebud]]'s Lakota cemetery. Philip James accompanied the repatriation.\n\nLittle Chief and Good Robe's eighteen-month-old son, Red Penny, who travelled in Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show is also buried here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rootschat.com/forum/index.php?topic=296911.27|title=The Salford Sioux \u2013 Manchester's own native American community (Lancashire) Page 4 RootsChat.Com|publisher=}}</ref> The resting place of Red Penny remain a mystery.\n\nTwo notable Polish figures originally buried in Brompton Cemetery were reburied in [[Powazki Cemetery]], [[Warsaw]]:\n*General [[Micha\u0142 Karaszewicz-Tokarzewski]] \u2013 founder of a Polish resistance unit in WWII and war hero, who died in [[Casablanca]] on 22 May 1964. The urn containing his ashes was reburied at Powazki in September 1992.\n*Major General [[Felicjan S\u0142awoj Sk\u0142adkowski]] \u2013 prime minister of [[Poland]] before outbreak of WWII, who died in London in August 1962, was reburied at Powazki on 8 June 1990.\n\n==Funerary art==\nThe richness of the art and symbolism contained in many graves traces art movements across two centuries. Aside from the stonemason's and sculptor's craft, there is a vast array of lettering, decorative ironwork (sadly in a very corroded state) and ceramics. Some graves and mausolea are the work of noted artists and architects.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nAlthough never envisaged as a park, [[John Claudius Loudon|JC Loudon]] devised the original planting scheme that was not fully realised. There are over 60 species of trees, of which the limes are dated to 1838. The fact of the enclosure of the cemetery by a wall, has preserved almost intact, a distinct area of Victorian country flora. Each season brings its features, like snow-drops and bluebells or wild lupin, broad-leaf pea and ferns. There are small scale wooded areas and meadows. Since the land was used for [[market garden]]s, there are wild cabbages, asparagus and garlic among the slabs. In Autumn, there can be a display of [[Fungiidae|fungi]], a [[Mycology|mycologist's]] trove. The evergreens and ivy are a haven for birds and countless insects. Over 200 species of moth and butterfly have been identified in the cemetery. Mammals are represented by bats, a range of rodents, including grey squirrels and several families of foxes. Among the birds, there are many garden species with the addition of [[European green woodpecker|green woodpecker]]s and occasionally, [[kestrel]]s. The macaws are only visitors.\n\n==Public access==\nThe cemetery is open daily to the public throughout the year, with opening times varying with the seasons. It is regularly visited by the [[Parks Police Service]] to monitor and curb occurrences of anti-social behaviour.\nDog walking and cycling, under strict control, is permitted on indicated paths. Through traffic is forbidden and there is no parking. Any visiting vehicles must observe a 5&nbsp;mph limit. The [[byelaws]] are displayed on boards at both entrances.\nThe Friends of Brompton Cemetery organise Open Days, regular tours and other public attractions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brompton-cemetery.org|title=The Friends of Brompton Cemetery}}</ref>\n\nThe cemetery has a reputation for being a popular [[Cruising for sex|cruising ground]] for gay men.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://qxmagazine.com/pdf/gayhistory-west.pdf|title=Go west, young man|work=QX Magazine International|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==A connection with Beatrix Potter==\n[[Image:Nutkins 002.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Nutkins gravestone]]\n\n[[Beatrix Potter]], who lived in Old Brompton Road nearby and enjoyed walking around it, may have taken the names of some of her characters from tombstones in the cemetery.  Names of people buried there included Mr. Nutkins, Mr. McGregor, Mr. Brock, Mr. Tod, Jeremiah Fisher and even a Peter Rabbett, although it is not known for certain if there were tombstones with these names.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thewestmorlandgazette.co.uk/archive/2001/08/03/The+Lake+District+Archive/6936235.Grave_inspiration_to_Beatrix__Potter/|title=Grave inspiration to Beatrix Potter|last=Barden|first=Karen|date=3 August 2001 |work=The Westmorland Gazette|publisher=Newsquest (North West) Ltd|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1335598/Beatrix-Potters-cast-list-found-on-headstones.html|last=Baker|first=Erin|date= 28 July 2001|work=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=25 May 2013|location=London|title=Beatrix Potter's cast list found on headstones}}</ref><ref>Mason, M. (2013). Walk the Lines: The London Underground, Overground. London: Arrow Books. p.174  {{ISBN|978-0-099-55793-7}}</ref>\n\n==Brompton Cemetery in film==\n\nBrompton Cemetery has featured in a number of films, including as the exterior of a Russian church in ''[[GoldenEye|Goldeneye]]'',<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/united-kingdom/england/london/articles/london-filming-locations/|title=The London filming locations you might not have known about|last=Smith|first=Oliver|date=4 October 2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> ''S[[Storm Breaker|tormbreaker]]'', ''[[Johnny English]]'' <ref name=\":0\" /> and ''[[The Wings of the Dove (1997 film)|The Wings of the Dove]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/brompton-cemetery/about-brompton-cemetery/brompton-cemetery-in-film|title=Brompton Cemetery in film|website=The Royal Parks|language=en|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Gate of Brompton Cemetery on the Old Brompton Road.JPG|Old Brompton Road entrance\nImage:001-brompton-cemetery-by William Cowen.jpg|001-brompton-cemetery-by William Cowen\nImage:Among the gravestones, Brompton Cemetery SW10 - geograph.org.uk - 1262459.jpg|Among the gravestones\nImage:Grave of John Snow.JPG|Monument to [[John Snow (physician)|John Snow]]\nImage:Grave of John Jackson.JPG|The lion on the grave of \"Gentleman\" [[John Jackson (English boxer)|John Jackson]]\nImage:Grave of Robert Coombes.JPG|Monument to [[Robert Coombes]] (on the right, now sadly defaced)\nImage:HenryMearsBrompton01.jpg|Monument to [[Gus Mears]], founder of [[Chelsea F.C.]] nearby\nImage:Brompton Cemetery, London 09.JPG|Brompton Cemetery bas-relief\nImage:Entry to the Catacombs.JPG|Entry to the catacombs\nImage:Chelsea Pensioners Memorial.JPG|[[Chelsea Pensioner]]s' Memorial\nImage:Brompton Cemetery, London 107.JPG|mausoleum, Brompton Cemetery\nImage:Central section, Brompton Cemetery.JPG|Central section\nImage:Brompton Cemetery - Parrot and Gravestones.jpg|Blue visitor among Gravestones\nImage:Brompton Cemetery SE Arcade 02.JPG|Brompton Cemetery SE Arcade\nImage:Old and new London - a narrative of its history, its people, and its places (1873) (14778032852).jpg|Fulham Road entrance (1873)\nImage:Brompton next to Stamford Bridge.JPG|Brompton Cemetery near Stamford Bridge stadium\nImage:Brompton Cemetery, London 75.JPG|portal, Brompton Cemetery\nImage:Central avenue, Brompton Cemetery.JPG|Central avenue, Brompton Cemetery\nImage:Walham Green and North End c.1860.jpg|Middlesex, detail of [[Fulham]] c.1860\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Magnificent Seven cemeteries]]\n*[[Funerary art]]\n*[[London Cemetery and Extension]]\n*[[Victorian cemetery]]\n*[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Meller, Hugh & Brian Parsons (2008). ''London Cemeteries: an illustrated guide and gazetteer'', The History Press. {{ISBN|978-0-7509-4622-3}}.\n* Beach, Darren (2008). ''London's Cemeteries''. Metro Guides. {{ISBN|1-902910-23-0}}\n* Culbertson, Judi & Tom Randall (1991). ''Permanent Londoners: An Illustrated Guide to the Cemeteries of London''. Post Mills, VT: Chelsea Green Publishing Company.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Brompton Cemetery}}\n* [https://brompton-cemetery.org.uk/ Friends of Brompton Cemetery] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071130001614/http://www.royalparks.org.uk/parks/brompton_cemetery/about.cfm Brompton Cemetery] (Royal Parks website)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071008230353/http://www.brompton.darkdestiny.co.uk/ Recent photos and information on Brompton Cemetery]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QMyW5W5CF10/ YouTube \u2013 Brompton Cemetery \u2013 Guided Tour \u2013 Introductory Talk]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060823091118/http://www.brompton.org/Residents.htm Brompton Cemetery. List of notable occupants.]\n{{LB Kensington and Chelsea}}\n{{Cemeteries in London}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:1839 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n[[Category:Burials at Brompton Cemetery|*]]\n[[Category:Anglican cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Royal Parks of London]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth War Graves Commission cemeteries in England]]\n[[Category:West Brompton]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed parks and gardens in London]]\n[[Category:Burial sites of the Spencer-Churchill family]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Reordered cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brompton_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "Wellcome Sanger Institute", "text_new": "{{short description|British genomics research institute}}\n{{Infobox Institute\n| name = Wellcome Sanger Institute\n| image = [[File:Sanger Logo.png]]\n| established = 1992\n| head_label = Director\n| head = [[Michael Stratton]]\n| president = \n| faculty = 32\n| staff = ~900\n| budget = \n| endowment = \n| debt = \n| city = [[Hinxton]]\n| state = [[Cambridgeshire]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| address = [[Wellcome Genome Campus]]\n| website = {{URL|sanger.ac.uk}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Wellcome Sanger Institute''', previously known as '''The Sanger Centre''' and '''Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute''', is a [[non-profit organisation|non-profit]] British [[genomics]] and [[genetics]] research institute, primarily funded by the [[Wellcome Trust]].<ref>\n{{cite web| url        = http://www.cggh.ox.ac.uk/?title=MRC_Centre_United_Kingdom#Wellcome_Trust_Sanger_Institute| title      = MRC Centre United Kingdom: Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute| publisher  = [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]]| accessdate = 2008-12-22}}</ref>\n\nIt is located on the [[Wellcome Genome Campus]] by the village of [[Hinxton]], outside [[Cambridge]]. It shares this location with the [[European Bioinformatics Institute]]. It was established in 1992 and named after double [[Nobel Laureate]], [[Frederick Sanger]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Walker | first1 = John| authorlink = John E. Walker| title = Frederick Sanger (1918\u20132013) Double Nobel-prizewinning genomics pioneer| doi = 10.1038/505027a | journal = Nature | volume = 505 | issue = 7481 | pages = 27 | year = 2014 | pmid =  24380948| pmc = | title-link = Frederick Sanger| doi-access = free }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Sanger | first1 = F. | doi = 10.1146/annurev.bi.57.070188.000245 | title = Sequences, Sequences, and Sequences | journal = Annual Review of Biochemistry | volume = 57 | pages = 1\u201329 | year = 1988 | pmid =  2460023| pmc = }}</ref> It was conceived as a large scale [[DNA sequencing]] centre to participate in the [[Human Genome Project]], and went on to make the largest single contribution to the gold standard sequence of the [[human genome]]. From its inception the Institute established and has maintained a policy of [[data sharing]], and does much of its research in [[collaboration]].\n\nSince 2000, the Institute expanded its mission to understand \"the role of genetics in health and disease\".<ref>\n{{cite web| url        = http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/| title      = Wellcome Sanger Institute - About us| publisher  = Wellcome Sanger Institute| accessdate = 2010-06-28}}</ref>  The Institute now employs around 900 people<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanger.ac.uk/people|title=Our People|last=www-core (webteam)|website=www.sanger.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> and engages in five main areas of research: Cancer, Ageing and Somatic Mutation; Cellular Genetics; Human Genetics; Parasite and Microbes; and the Tree of Life.\n\n==Facilities and resources==\n\n===Campus===\n[[File:Sanger Institute and Hinxton Hall, Cambridge, UK.jpg|300px|thumb|The Wellcome Genome Campus]]\n[[File:DNA Helix and Tree of Life stain glass window.JPG|thumbnail|right|Commemorative stain window located in the Sulston building of the Wellcome Sanger Institute, to mark the opening of the Genome Campus.]]\nIn 1993 the then 17 Sanger Centre staff moved into temporary laboratory space at Hinxton Hall in [[Cambridgeshire]].<ref name=\"sanger1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/history/history.html|title=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute - History|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>\nThis {{convert|55|acre|m2|adj=on}} site was to become the Wellcome Genome Campus, which has a growing population of around 1300 staff, approximately 900 of whom work at the Sanger Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/careers/|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - Work and study|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> The Genome Campus also includes the Wellcome Trust Conference Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtconference.org/|title=Welcome to the Wellcome Genome Campus Conference Centre|author=|date=|website=Wellcome Genome Campus Conference Centre|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>  and the [[European Bioinformatics Institute]]. A major extension of the campus was officially opened in 2005;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/Info/Press/2005/051014.shtml|title=Wellcome Trust Genome Campus Extension Opened: Visit by Her Royal Highness, The Princess Royal|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> the buildings accommodate new laboratories, a [[data centre]] and staff amenities.<ref name=datacentre>{{Cite journal | last1 = Doctorow | first1 = C. | authorlink1 = Cory Doctorow| title = Big data: Welcome to the petacentre | doi = 10.1038/455016a | journal = Nature | volume = 455 | issue = 7209 | pages = 16\u201321 | year = 2008 | pmid =  18769411| pmc = | doi-access = free }}</ref> In discussing the name of the centre, Sanger (still alive when the centre was opened) told [[John Sulston]], the founding director, that the centre \"had better be good.\" Sulston commented, \"I rather wished I hadn\u2019t asked.\"<ref name=\"Interview with John Sulston\">{{cite web|last1=Sulston|first1=John|title=Interview with John Sulston|url=http://library.cshl.edu/oralhistory/interview/scientific-experience/molecular-biologists/sulston-frederick-sanger/|publisher=Cold Spring Harbor Laboratories digital archive|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Sequencing===\nThe Sanger Institute's sequencing staff handle millions of [[DNA]] samples each week.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} The Institute \"capitalises on leading-edge technologies to answer questions unanswerable only a few years ago\".<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.sanger.ac.uk/resources/technologies/sequencing.html|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - Sequencing|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> The advances in technology allow the Sanger Institute to carry out sequencing  of the genomes of individual humans, [[vertebrate]] [[species]] and [[pathogens]], at an ever-increasing pace and reducing cost. The Institute has more than 100 ongoing pathogen sequencing projects.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/projects/pathogengenomics/|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - Pathogen genomics|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> The output of the Sanger Institute is around 10 billion [[base pair|bases]] of raw sequence data per day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellcome.ac.uk/News/2008/Features/WTX052290.htm|author=Jones, I|title=Feature: Highly cited|publisher=Wellcome Trust|accessdate=2009-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Scientific resources===\n{{Update|section|date=April 2015}}\n[[Bioinformatic]] databases resources are one of the outcomes of research programmes that the Sanger Institute is involved in. Those hosted by the Sanger Institute include:\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[COSMIC cancer database|COSMIC]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 25355519| pmc = 4383913| year = 2015| last1 = Forbes| first1 = S. A.| title = COSMIC: Exploring the world's knowledge of somatic mutations in human cancer| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 43| issue = Database issue| pages = D805\u201311| last2 = Beare| first2 = D| last3 = Gunasekaran| first3 = P| last4 = Leung| first4 = K| last5 = Bindal| first5 = N| last6 = Boutselakis| first6 = H| last7 = Ding| first7 = M| last8 = Bamford| first8 = S| last9 = Cole| first9 = C| last10 = Ward| first10 = S| last11 = Kok| first11 = C. Y.| last12 = Jia| first12 = M| last13 = De| first13 = T| last14 = Teague| first14 = J. W.| last15 = Stratton| first15 = M. R. | authorlink15 = Michael Stratton| last16 = McDermott| first16 = U| last17 = Campbell| first17 = P. J.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gku1075}} {{open access}}</ref> a catalogue of [[Somatic (biology)|somatic]] mutations in cancer\n* [[DECIPHER]], a database of chromosomal imbalance and [[phenotype]] in humans, using Ensembl resources<ref name=decipher>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24150940| pmc = 3965078| year = 2014| last1 = Bragin| first1 = E| title = DECIPHER: Database for the interpretation of phenotype-linked plausibly pathogenic sequence and copy-number variation| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D993\u2013D1000| last2 = Chatzimichali| first2 = E. A.| last3 = Wright| first3 = C. F.| last4 = Hurles| first4 = M. E.| last5 = Firth| first5 = H. V.| last6 = Bevan| first6 = A. P.| last7 = Swaminathan| first7 = G. J.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt937}}</ref>\n* [[Ensembl]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 25352552| year = 2015| last1 = Cunningham| first1 = F| title = Ensembl 2015| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 43| issue = Database issue| pages = D662\u20139| last2 = Amode| first2 = M. R.| last3 = Barrell| first3 = D| last4 = Beal| first4 = K| last5 = Billis| first5 = K| last6 = Brent| first6 = S| last7 = Carvalho-Silva| first7 = D| last8 = Clapham| first8 = P| last9 = Coates| first9 = G| last10 = Fitzgerald| first10 = S| last11 = Gil| first11 = L| last12 = Gir\u00f3n| first12 = C. G.| last13 = Gordon| first13 = L| last14 = Hourlier| first14 = T| last15 = Hunt| first15 = S. E.| last16 = Janacek| first16 = S. H.| last17 = Johnson| first17 = N| last18 = Juettemann| first18 = T| last19 = K\u00e4h\u00e4ri| first19 = A. K.| last20 = Keenan| first20 = S| last21 = Martin| first21 = F. J.| last22 = Maurel| first22 = T| last23 = McLaren| first23 = W| last24 = Murphy| first24 = D. N.| last25 = Nag| first25 = R| last26 = Overduin| first26 = B| last27 = Parker| first27 = A| last28 = Patricio| first28 = M| last29 = Perry| first29 = E| last30 = Pignatelli| first30 = M| display-authors = 29| doi = 10.1093/nar/gku1010 | pmc=4383879}}</ref> a genome browser co-hosted by the European Bioinformatics Institute.\n* GeneDB,<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 22116062| pmc = 3245030| year = 2012| last1 = Logan-Klumpler| first1 = F. J.| title = GeneDB--an annotation database for pathogens| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 40| issue = Database issue| pages = D98\u2013108| last2 = De Silva| first2 = N| last3 = Boehme| first3 = U| last4 = Rogers| first4 = M. B.| last5 = Velarde| first5 = G| last6 = McQuillan| first6 = J. A.| last7 = Carver| first7 = T| last8 = Aslett| first8 = M| last9 = Olsen| first9 = C| last10 = Subramanian| first10 = S| last11 = Phan| first11 = I| last12 = Farris| first12 = C| last13 = Mitra| first13 = S| last14 = Ramasamy| first14 = G| last15 = Wang| first15 = H| last16 = Tivey| first16 = A| last17 = Jackson| first17 = A| last18 = Houston| first18 = R| last19 = Parkhill| first19 = J| last20 = Holden| first20 = M| last21 = Harb| first21 = O. S.| last22 = Brunk| first22 = B. P.| last23 = Myler| first23 = P. J.| last24 = Roos| first24 = D| last25 = Carrington| first25 = M| last26 = Smith| first26 = D. F.| last27 = Hertz-Fowler| first27 = C| last28 = Berriman| first28 = M| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkr1032}}</ref> a [[pathogen]] sequence database\n* [[Mouse Genetics Project]], including a database of standardised phenotypic analysis for many hundreds of mutant mice.\n* [[Vertebrate and Genome Annotation Project|Vega]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 18003653| pmc = 2238886| year = 2008| last1 = Wilming| first1 = L. G.| title = The vertebrate genome annotation (Vega) database| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 36| issue = Database issue| pages = D753\u201360| last2 = Gilbert| first2 = J. G.| last3 = Howe| first3 = K| last4 = Trevanion| first4 = S| last5 = Hubbard| first5 = T| last6 = Harrow| first6 = J. L.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkm987}}</ref> a vertebrate genome annotation resource\n{{colend}}\n\nSeveral databases were initiated at the Sanger Institute but are now hosted elsewhere:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[MEROPS]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24157837| pmc = 3964991| year = 2014| last1 = Rawlings| first1 = N. D.| title = MEROPS: The database of proteolytic enzymes, their substrates and inhibitors| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D503\u20139| last2 = Waller| first2 = M| last3 = Barrett| first3 = A. J.| last4 = Bateman| first4 = A| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt953}}</ref> a [[peptidase]] database\n* [[Pfam]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24288371| pmc = 3965110| year = 2014| last1 = Finn| first1 = R. D.| title = Pfam: The protein families database| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D222\u201330| last2 = Bateman| first2 = A | authorlink2 = Alex Bateman| last3 = Clements| first3 = J| last4 = Coggill| first4 = P| last5 = Eberhardt| first5 = R. Y.| last6 = Eddy| first6 = S. R. | authorlink6 = Sean Eddy| last7 = Heger| first7 = A| last8 = Hetherington| first8 = K| last9 = Holm| first9 = L| last10 = Mistry| first10 = J| last11 = Sonnhammer| first11 = E. L.| last12 = Tate| first12 = J| last13 = Punta| first13 = M| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt1223}} {{open access}}</ref> a [[protein family]] database\n* [[Rfam]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 25392425| pmc = 4383904| year = 2015| last1 = Nawrocki| first1 = E. P.| title = Rfam 12.0: Updates to the RNA families database| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 43| issue = Database issue| pages = D130\u20137| last2 = Burge| first2 = S. W.| last3 = Bateman| first3 = A| last4 = Daub| first4 = J| last5 = Eberhardt| first5 = R. Y.| last6 = Eddy| first6 = S. R.| last7 = Floden| first7 = E. W.| last8 = Gardner| first8 = P. P.| last9 = Jones| first9 = T. A.| last10 = Tate| first10 = J| last11 = Finn| first11 = R. D.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gku1063}}</ref> an [[RNA]] family database\n* [[TreeFam]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24194607| pmc = 3965059| year = 2014| last1 = Schreiber| first1 = F| title = Tree ''Fam'' v9: A new website, more species and orthology-on-the-fly| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D922\u20135| last2 = Patricio| first2 = M| last3 = Muffato| first3 = M| last4 = Pignatelli| first4 = M| last5 = Bateman| first5 = A| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt1055}}</ref> a database of [[phylogenetic]] trees for animal genes\n* [[WormBase]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24194605| pmc = 3965043| year = 2014| last1 = Harris| first1 = T. W.| title = Worm ''Base'' 2014: New views of curated biology| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D789\u201393| last2 = Baran| first2 = J| last3 = Bieri| first3 = T| last4 = Cabunoc| first4 = A| last5 = Chan| first5 = J| last6 = Chen| first6 = W. J.| last7 = Davis| first7 = P| last8 = Done| first8 = J| last9 = Grove| first9 = C| last10 = Howe| first10 = K| last11 = Kishore| first11 = R| last12 = Lee| first12 = R| last13 = Li| first13 = Y| last14 = Muller| first14 = H. M.| last15 = Nakamura| first15 = C| last16 = Ozersky| first16 = P| last17 = Paulini| first17 = M| last18 = Raciti| first18 = D| last19 = Schindelman| first19 = G| last20 = Tuli| first20 = M. A.| last21 = Van Auken| first21 = K| last22 = Wang| first22 = D| last23 = Wang| first23 = X| last24 = Williams| first24 = G| last25 = Wong| first25 = J. D.| last26 = Yook| first26 = K| last27 = Schedl| first27 = T| last28 = Hodgkin| first28 = J| last29 = Berriman| first29 = M| last30 = Kersey| first30 = P| display-authors = 29| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt1063}}</ref> a database on the biology and sequence of the [[model organism]] ''[[Caenorhabditis elegans|C. elegans]]'' and other related Nematodes.\n* [[WormBase ParaSite]], a database for the genomics for parasitic [[helminths]] (both Nematodes and Platyhelminthes).\n{{colend}}\n\n==Research==\n[[File:Hinxton hall.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Morgan Building (right), part of the Sanger Institute]]\n\nScientific research at the Sanger Institute is organised into five Scientific Programmes, each defining a major area of research with a particular biological, disease or analytic focus. The current Programmes at the Sanger Institute are Cancer, Ageing and Somatic Mutation, Cellular Genetics, Human Genetics, Parasites and Microbes and Tree of Life. Studies from all programmes provide insights into human, pathogen, cellular evolution, the phenotypic and hence biological consequences of genome variation and the processes which cause mutations.\n\n===Cancer, Ageing and Somatic Mutation Programme===\nProvides leadership in data aggregation and informatics innovation, develops high-throughput cellular models of cancer for genome-wide functional screens and drug testing, and explores somatic mutation's role in clonal evolution, ageing and development. This Programme includes the [[Cancer Genome Project]].\n\n===Cellular Genetics Programme===\nExplores human gene function by studying the impact of genome variation on cell biology. Large-scale systematic screens are used to discover the impact of naturally occurring and engineered genome mutations in human induced pluripotent cells (hIPSCs), their differentiated derivatives and other cell types. It is one of the founder programmes driving the creation and organisation of the international [[Human Cell Atlas]] initiative.\n\n===Human Genetics Programme===\nThe Institute's research in [[human genetics]] focuses on the characterisation of [[human genetic variation]] in health and disease. Aside from the Institute's contribution to the [[Human Genome Project]], researchers at the Sanger Institute have made contributions in various research areas relating to disease, population comparative and [[Extended evolutionary synthesis|evolutionary genetics]]. In January 2008, the launch of the [[1000 Genomes Project]], a collaboration with scientists around the globe, signalled an effort to sequence the genomes of 1000 individuals in order to create the \"most detailed map of human genetic variation to support disease studies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1000genomes.org/page.php|title=1000 Genomes: A Deep Catalog of Human Genetic Variation|publisher=1000 Genomes Project|accessdate=2008-12-22}}</ref> The data from the pilot projects was made freely available in public databases in June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/press/2010/100621.html|title=1000 Genomes Project releases data from pilot projects on path to providing database for 2,500 human genomes|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> In 2010, the Sanger Institute announced its participation in the UK10K project,<ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 24424120\n| pmc = 4026295\n| year = 2014\n| last1 = Kaye\n| first1 = J\n| title = Managing clinically significant findings in research: The UK10K example\n| journal = European Journal of Human Genetics\n| volume = 22\n| issue = 9\n| pages = 1100\u20134\n| last2 = Hurles\n| first2 = M\n| last3 = Griffin\n| first3 = H\n| last4 = Grewal\n| first4 = J\n| last5 = Bobrow\n| first5 = M | authorlink5 = Martin Bobrow\n| last6 = Timpson\n| first6 = N\n| last7 = Smee\n| first7 = C\n| last8 = Bolton\n| first8 = P\n| last9 = Durbin\n| first9 = R | authorlink9 = Richard M. Durbin\n| last10 = Dyke\n| first10 = S\n| last11 = Fitzpatrick\n| first11 = D\n| last12 = Kennedy\n| first12 = K\n| last13 = Kent\n| first13 = A\n| last14 = Muddyman\n| first14 = D\n| last15 = Muntoni\n| first15 = F\n| last16 = Raymond\n| first16 = L. F.\n| last17 = Semple\n| first17 = R\n| last18 = Spector\n| first18 = T\n| last19 = Uk\n| first19 = 10K\n| doi = 10.1038/ejhg.2013.290\n}} {{open access}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 24229443\n| pmc = 3978569\n| year = 2013\n| last1 = Muddyman\n| first1 = D\n| title = Implementing a successful data-management framework: The UK10K managed access model\n| journal = Genome Medicine\n| volume = 5\n| issue = 11\n| pages = 100\n| last2 = Smee\n| first2 = C\n| last3 = Griffin\n| first3 = H\n| last4 = Kaye\n| first4 = J\n| doi = 10.1186/gm504\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/press/2010/100624-uk10k.html|title=Wellcome Trust launches study of 10,000 human genomes in UK|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> which will sequence the genomes of 10,000 individuals to identify rare genetic variants and their effects on human health. The Sanger Institute is also part of the [[International Cancer Genome Consortium]], an international effort to describe different cancer [[tumour]] types.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icgc.org/|title=International Cancer Genome Consortium Homepage|publisher=International Cancer Genome Consortium|accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref> It is also part of the [[GENCODE]] and [[ENCODE]] research programmes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/resources/databases/encode//|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - ENCODE and GENCODE|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> to create an encyclopaedia of DNA elements.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe Programme applies genomics to population-scale studies to identify the causal variants and pathways involved in human disease and their effects on cell biology. It also models developmental disorders to explore which physical aspects might be reversible.\n\n===Pathogens and Microbes Programme===\nInvestigates the common underpinning mechanisms of evolution, infection and resistance to therapy into bolster understanding of [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es and [[parasitism|parasites]], with a particular interest in [[malaria]]. It also explores the effects of genome variation on the biology of [[host (biology)|host]]-[[pathogen]] interactions, in particular host response to infection and the role of microiotia in health and disease. All the genomes after sequencing are made available at the web-based onsite-maintained database, GeneDB.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n=== Tree of Life Programme ===\nThe Tree of Life Programme was created in 2019 to investigate the diversity of complex organisms found in the UK through sequencing and cellular technologies. It also compares and contrasts species' genome sequences to unlock insights into evolution and conservation. This Programme will play a leading role in the Darwin Tree of Life Project, a UK-wide initiative to sequence the genomes of all 66,000 complex species (eukaryotes) in the British Isles.\n\n===Collaborations===\nMuch of the Sanger Institute's research is carried out in partnership with the wider [[scientific community]]; over 90 percent of the Institute's research papers involve collaborations with other organisations.<ref>Figure based on data for 2008 retrieved from SCOPUS website</ref> Significant collaborations include:\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[1000 Genomes Project]]\n* [[GENCODE]] and [[ENCODE]] (ENCyclopedia Of DNA Elements)\n* [[International Cancer Genome Consortium]]\n* [[International HapMap Project]]<ref>{{Cite journal| last1 = - | first1 = -| last2 = Gibbs | first2 = R. A. | last3 = Belmont | first3 = J. W. | last4 = Hardenbol | first4 = P. | last5 = Willis | first5 = T. D. | last6 = Yu | first6 = F. | last7 = Yang | first7 = H. | last8 = Ch'Ang | first8 = L. Y. | last9 = Huang | first9 = W. | doi = 10.1038/nature02168| last10 = Liu | first10 = B.| last11 = Shen | first11 = Y.| last12 = Tam | first12 = P. K. H.| last13 = Tsui | first13 = L. C.| last14 = Waye | first14 = M. M. Y.| last15 = Wong | first15 = J. T. F.| last16 = Zeng | first16 = C.| last17 = Zhang | first17 = Q.| last18 = Chee | first18 = M. S.| last19 = Galver | first19 = L. M.| last20 = Kruglyak | first20 = S.| last21 = Murray | first21 = S. S.| last22 = Oliphant | first22 = A. R.| last23 = Montpetit | first23 = A.| last24 = Hudson | first24 = T. J.| last25 = Chagnon | first25 = F.| last26 = Ferretti | first26 = V.| last27 = Leboeuf | first27 = M.| last28 = Phillips | first28 = M. S.| last29 = Verner | first29 = A.| last30 = Kwok | first30 = P. Y. | title = The International HapMap Project | journal = Nature | volume = 426 | issue = 6968 | pages = 789\u2013796 | year = 2003 | pmid = 14685227 | pmc = | url = https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/62838/1/nature02168.pdf|hdl = 2027.42/62838| bibcode = 2003Natur.426..789G| displayauthors = 29}}</ref>\n* [[International Knockout Mouse Consortium]]\n* [[International Mouse Phenotyping Consortium]]\n* SNP ([[Single nucleotide polymorphism]]) Consortium\n* The Copy Number Variation Project<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/humgen/cnv/|title=Programmes - Wellcome Sanger Institute|first=www-core|last=(webteam)|date=|website=www.sanger.ac.uk|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref> \n* The [[genome sequencing]] of ''[[Schizosaccharomyces pombe|S. pombe]]'', ''[[Caenorhabditis elegans|C. elegans]]'', [[mouse]] and the [[Malaria]] parasite.\n* The [[Human Genome Project]]\n* The UK 10,000 Genomes Project (UK10K)<ref>[http://www.uk10k.org/ UK10K] (the UK 10,000 Genomes Project)</ref> \n* [[Wellcome Trust]] - [[Department of Biotechnology]], [[India]] Alliance<ref>http://www.wellcomedbt.org/Mini_symposium_final_poster_schedule.pdf</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n===Public engagement===\n[[File:Sanger Institute outreach DNA bracelets.jpg|thumb|Children at a public outreach event thread bracelets in four colours to spell out a DNA sequence.]]\nThe Sanger Institute has a programme of [[public engagement]] activity. The programme aims to make complex biomedical research accessible to a range of audiences including school students and their teachers, and local community members.\n\nThe Communication and Public Engagement programme aims to \"encourage informed discussion about issues relevant to Sanger Institute research\"<ref name=\"Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute\" /> and \"foster a community of researchers who can engage effectively with different audiences\".<ref name=\"Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/Teams/Team104/|title=Team 104: Communication and Public Engagement Programme|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2009-01-12}}</ref> The Institute hosts visits for more than 1,500 students, teachers and community groups per year. Visitors may meet scientific staff, tour the Institute and its facilities, and participate in ethical debates and activities. The programme also offers professional development sessions for teachers of [[GCSE]] and post 16 science through the national network of [[Science Learning Centres]], and by hosting visits for groups interested in updating their knowledge in contemporary genetics. [[Videoconferencing]] into the Sanger Institute is also offered for Science Learning Centres, Science Centres and schools.\n\nScientific and public engagement staff also collaborate on and contribute to national projects such as the UK's ''InsideDNA''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidedna.org.uk/content/|title=InsideDNA|author=|date=|website=insidedna.org.uk|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>  traveling exhibition and the ''Who am I?'' gallery at [[Science Museum (London)|The Science Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/|title=Home - Science Museum|author=|date=|website=Science Museum|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref> They also participate in public events such as the Cambridge Science Festival.\n\n===Graduate training===\nThe Institute operates two PhD training programmes: a four-year course for basic science graduates, and a three-year course for clinicians. The four-year course requires students to rotate around three different laboratories in order to broaden their scientific horizons before choosing a PhD project. Each student is required to choose at least one experimental and one informatics-based rotation project.<ref>\n{{cite web| url        = http://www.sanger.ac.uk/careers/phd/| title      = Wellcome Sanger Institute PhD Programmes| publisher  = Wellcome Sanger Institute| accessdate = 2009-11-13}}</ref> Institute houses approximately 50 pre-doctoral students, all of whom are registered at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407104250/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/publications/theses.html|title=Sanger PhD and MPhil theses|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/publications/theses.html|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Officers==\nAccording to Companies House the five officers of the parent company Genome Research Limited are Henry Parkinson, Kay Elizabeth Davies, Rolf Dieter Heuer, James Cuthbert Smith, David Lindsay Willetts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/02742969/officers |title=GENOME RESEARCH LIMITED - Officers}}</ref> According to the Sanger website Henry Parkinson is head of legal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sanger.ac.uk/people/directory/parkinson-henry}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n\n{{As of|2015}} the Sanger employs around 900 people, and is led by [[Michael Stratton]]. Notable scientific staff, [[Faculty (academic staff)|faculty]] and alumni are listed below:\n\n===Academic faculty===\n{{As of|2019}} a faculty of 32 scientists lead [[hypothesis]]-driven research, seeking answers to biomedical questions.<ref name=faculty>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316171820/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/|title=Sanger Faculty|archivedate=2015-03-16}}</ref> Among others, these include [[Dominic Kwiatkowski]], [[Nicole Soranzo]], [[Michael Stratton]], [[Sarah Teichmann]] and [[Matthew Hurles]]. The institute also has a number of Associate Faculty members, International Fellows and Honorary Faculty. These include [[Adrian Bird]], [[Ewan Birney]], [[Chris Ponting]], [[Fiona Powrie]], [[Stephen O'Rahilly]] and [[Wolf Reik]], among others.\n\n===Scientific advisory board===\n\nThe Sanger [[Board of directors|Board of Management]] are guided by the scientific [[advisory board]]<ref name=sab>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407104047/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/people/advisory.html|title=Sanger Advisory Board|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/people/advisory.html|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref> whose members include Professor [[David Altshuler (physician)|David Altshuler]], Professor [[Anton Berns]], Professor [[David J. Lipman]], Professor Kevin Marsh and Professor Sir [[Paul Nurse]].\n\n===Alumni===\nPrevious faculty members at the Sanger include:<ref name=alumni>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407104218/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/previousfaculty/|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/previousfaculty/|title=Previous faculty at the Sanger|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n*[[Alex Bateman]], [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory|EMBL]]-[[European Bioinformatics Institute|EBI]]<ref name=wiki>{{Cite journal | last1 = Logan | first1 = D. W. | last2 = Sandal | first2 = M. | last3 = Gardner | first3 = P. P. | authorlink3  =| last4 = Manske | first4 = M. | authorlink4 = Magnus Manske| last5 = Bateman | first5 = A. | authorlink5 =  Alex Bateman| title = Ten Simple Rules for Editing Wikipedia | doi = 10.1371/journal.pcbi.1000941 | journal = [[PLOS Computational Biology]] | volume = 6 | issue = 9 | pages = e1000941 | year = 2010 | pmid =  20941386| pmc =2947980 | bibcode = 2010PLSCB...6E0941L }} {{open access}}</ref>\n* [[Tim Hubbard]], Professor at [[King's College London]]\n* [[Leena Peltonen-Palotie]] (1952 \u2013  2010)<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = van Ommen | first1 = Gertjan| title = Obituary: Leena Peltonen-Palotie (1952\u20132010) A visionary in medical genetics.| doi = 10.1038/464992a | journal = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]| volume = 464 | issue = 7291 | pages = 992 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20393553| pmc = | title-link = Leena Peltonen-Palotie}}</ref>\n* [[Julian Rayner]] \n* [[Eleftheria Zeggini]]\n* [[Richard M. Durbin|Richard Durbin]] FRS\n\n{{colend}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:EBI and Sanger Center, Genome campus, Cambridgeshire.jpg|350px|right|thumb|The Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute was established in 1992, funded by the [[Wellcome Trust]] and the UK's [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]]]]\n\n===Management ===\n[[John E. Sulston]] was the founding Director of the Sanger Institute. Sulston was instrumental in the choice of the Hinxton site for the Institute and remained there as Director until the announcement of the completion of the draft human genome in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genome.gov/10001457|title=International Human Genome Sequencing Consortium Announces \"Working Draft\" of Human Genome|publisher=National Human Genome Research Institute|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> Sulston graduated from the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1963 and completed his PhD on the chemical synthesis of DNA in 1966.<ref>{{cite book|author=Sulston J, Ferry G|title=The Common Thread: A story of Science, Politics, Ethics, and the Human Genome|year=2002|publisher=The Joseph Henry Press|page=18}}</ref> He shared the 2002 [[Nobel Prize]] in Physiology or Medicine with [[Robert Horvitz]] and [[Sydney Brenner]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/2002/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 2002|publisher=Nobel Prize|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> two years after standing down as Director of the Institute.\n\nIn 2000, [[Allan Bradley]] left his appointment as Professor at the [[Baylor College of Medicine]], in the US, to take up the position as Director of the Sanger Institute. Bradley wanted to build on the achievements made by the Sanger Institute in the Human Genome Project by \"concentrating on gene function, cancer genomics, and the genomes of model organisms such as the mouse and the zebrafish\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genomebiology.com/researchnews/default.asp?arx_id=gb-spotlight-20011106-02 |title=Sanger Institute looks to the future |publisher=Genome Biology |accessdate=2008-12-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040119195438/http://genomebiology.com/researchnews/default.asp?arx_id=gb-spotlight-20011106-02 |archivedate=January 19, 2004 }}</ref> Bradley received his BA, MA and PhD in Genetics from the University of Cambridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/Teams/faculty/bradley/|title=Professor Allan Bradley|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|archivedate=2015-04-07|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407061817/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/abradley/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 10839511| year = 2000| last1 = Gura| first1 = T| title = Changing of the guard: Allan Bradley is to head the Sanger Centre, a powerhouse of the Human Genome Project| journal = Nature| volume = 405| issue = 6785| pages = 389| doi = 10.1038/35013238}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 11606985| year = 2001| last1 = Adam| first1 = D| title = Sanger Centre welcomes gene funds with a new name| journal = Nature| volume = 413| issue = 6857| pages = 660| doi = 10.1038/35099707| bibcode = 2001Natur.413R.660A| doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 10830929| year = 2000| last1 = Dickson| first1 = D| title = Geneticist from Baylor named as new head of UK's Sanger Centre| journal = Nature| volume = 405| issue = 6784| pages = 264| doi = 10.1038/35012766| doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Bradley stepped down from his leadership role to form a [[startup company]], but remains on the faculty of the Institute as Director Emeritus. [[Michael Stratton|Mike Stratton]], who is a leader of the [[Cancer Genome Project]] and the [[International Cancer Genome Consortium]], was appointed Director of the Sanger Institute in May of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/press/2010/100517.html |title=Professor Mike Stratton appointed new Director|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref>\n\n===Human Genome Project===\nThe Sanger Institute was opened in 1993, three years after the inception of the [[Human Genome Project]], and went on to make the largest single contribution to the gold standard sequence of the [[human genome]], published in 2004.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Human Genome Sequencing Consortium|title=Finishing the euchromatic sequence of the human genome|journal=Nature|year=2004|volume=431|pages=931\u2013945|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v431/n7011/index.html|doi=10.1038/nature03001|pmid=15496913|issue=7011|bibcode=2004Natur.431..931H|doi-access=free}}</ref> The Institute was engaged in collaborations to sequence 8 of the 23 human pairs of [[chromosomes]] ([[chromosome 1|1]], [[chromosome 6|6]], [[chromosome 9|9]], [[chromosome 10|10]], [[chromosome 13|13]], [[chromosome 20|20]], [[chromosome 22|22]], and [[X chromosome|X]]).<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pennisi E|title=Reaching Their Goal Early, Sequencing Labs Celebrate|journal=Science|year=2003|volume=300|page=409|doi=10.1126/science.300.5618.409|pmid=12702850|issue=5618}}</ref> Since the publishing of the human genome, research carried out at the Institute has developed beyond sequencing of organisms into various biomedical research areas, including studies into diseases such as cancer, malaria and diabetes.\n\n==Controversy==\nIn August 2018 it was reported that an investigation was under way into allegations of bullying of staff and gender discrimination made against senior management of the [[Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute]], including the director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/aug/29/wellcome-sanger-institute-bosses-accused-bullying-staff|title=Bosses at leading UK science institute accused of bullying staff|last=Marsh|first=Sarah|last2=Devlin|first2=Hannah|date=2018-08-29|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> The investigation, carried out by the barrister Thomas Kibling from [[Matrix Chambers]], concluded in October 2018 and cleared Stratton of any wrongdoing, while listing areas for improvement in the workings of the Sanger Institute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanger.ac.uk/news/view/result-independent-investigation-whistleblowing-allegations-released |title=Result of independent investigation into whistleblowing allegations released |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2018-10-31|website=Sanger Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanger.ac.uk/sites/default/files/Oct2018/Thomas_Kibling_Investigatory_Report_-_Introduction_and_Executive_Summary.pdf |title=Thomas Kibling's Investigatory Report |author=Thomas Kibling |date=2018-10-31|website=Sanger Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-10-31}}</ref> The findings and the independence of the investigation were disputed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-018-07339-4 |title=Sanger whistle-blowers dispute findings that cleared management of bullying |date=2018-11-08}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019 it was reported that the institute had manufactured a medical tool with the intent of monetising it despite not having ethical nor legal approval to do so and having been made aware by [[Stellenbosch University]] and internal whistleblowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/genetics-lab-told-to-hand-back-african-tribes-dna-83xqls5sh |title=Genetics lab told to hand back African tribes' DNA}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{URL|sanger.ac.uk}}\n\n{{bioinformatics}}\n{{Wellcome Trust}}\n{{coord|52|05|N|0|11|E|region:GB_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Partner institutions of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Genetic engineering in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Genetics or genomics research institutions]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:South Cambridgeshire District]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British genomics research institute}}\n{{Infobox Institute\n| name        = Wellcome Sanger Institute\n| image       = [[File:Sanger Logo.png]]\n| established = 1992\n| head_label  = Director\n| head        = [[Michael Stratton]]\n| president   =\n| faculty     = 32\n| staff       = ~900{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n| budget      =\n| endowment   =\n| debt        =\n| city        = [[Hinxton]]\n| state       = [[Cambridgeshire]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| address     = [[Wellcome Genome Campus]]\n| website     = {{URL|sanger.ac.uk}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Wellcome Sanger Institute''', previously known as '''The Sanger Centre''' and '''Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute''', is a [[non-profit organisation|non-profit]] British [[genomics]] and [[genetics]] research institute, primarily funded by the [[Wellcome Trust]].<ref>\n{{cite web| url        = http://www.cggh.ox.ac.uk/?title=MRC_Centre_United_Kingdom#Wellcome_Trust_Sanger_Institute| title      = MRC Centre United Kingdom: Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute| publisher  = [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]]| accessdate = 2008-12-22}}</ref>\n\nIt is located on the [[Wellcome Genome Campus]] by the village of [[Hinxton]], outside [[Cambridge]]. It shares this location with the [[European Bioinformatics Institute]]. It was established in 1992 and named after double [[Nobel Laureate]], [[Frederick Sanger]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Walker | first1 = John| authorlink = John E. Walker| title = Frederick Sanger (1918\u20132013) Double Nobel-prizewinning genomics pioneer| doi = 10.1038/505027a | journal = Nature | volume = 505 | issue = 7481 | pages = 27 | year = 2014 | pmid =  24380948| pmc = | title-link = Frederick Sanger| doi-access = free }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Sanger | first1 = F. | doi = 10.1146/annurev.bi.57.070188.000245 | title = Sequences, Sequences, and Sequences | journal = Annual Review of Biochemistry | volume = 57 | pages = 1\u201329 | year = 1988 | pmid =  2460023| pmc = }}</ref> It was conceived as a large scale [[DNA sequencing]] centre to participate in the [[Human Genome Project]], and went on to make the largest single contribution to the gold standard sequence of the [[human genome]]. From its inception the Institute established and has maintained a policy of [[data sharing]], and does much of its research in [[collaboration]].\n\nSince 2000, the Institute expanded its mission to understand \"the role of genetics in health and disease\".<ref>\n{{cite web| url        = http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/| title      = Wellcome Sanger Institute - About us| publisher  = Wellcome Sanger Institute| accessdate = 2010-06-28}}</ref>  The Institute now employs around 900 people{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} and engages in five main areas of research: Cancer, Ageing and Somatic Mutation; Cellular Genetics; Human Genetics; Parasite and Microbes; and the Tree of Life.\n\n==Facilities and resources==\n\n===Campus===\n[[File:Sanger Institute and Hinxton Hall, Cambridge, UK.jpg|300px|thumb|The Wellcome Genome Campus]]\n[[File:DNA Helix and Tree of Life stain glass window.JPG|thumbnail|right|Commemorative stain window located in the Sulston building of the Wellcome Sanger Institute, to mark the opening of the Genome Campus.]]\nIn 1993 the then 17 Sanger Centre staff moved into temporary laboratory space at Hinxton Hall in [[Cambridgeshire]].<ref name=\"sanger1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/history/history.html|title=Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute - History|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref>\nThis {{convert|55|acre|m2|adj=on}} site was to become the Wellcome Genome Campus, which has a growing population of around 1300 staff, approximately 900 of whom work at the Sanger Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/careers/|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - Work and study|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> The Genome Campus also includes the Wellcome Trust Conference Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtconference.org/|title=Welcome to the Wellcome Genome Campus Conference Centre|author=|date=|website=Wellcome Genome Campus Conference Centre|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>  and the [[European Bioinformatics Institute]]. A major extension of the campus was officially opened in 2005;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/Info/Press/2005/051014.shtml|title=Wellcome Trust Genome Campus Extension Opened: Visit by Her Royal Highness, The Princess Royal|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> the buildings accommodate new laboratories, a [[data centre]] and staff amenities.<ref name=datacentre>{{Cite journal | last1 = Doctorow | first1 = C. | authorlink1 = Cory Doctorow| title = Big data: Welcome to the petacentre | doi = 10.1038/455016a | journal = Nature | volume = 455 | issue = 7209 | pages = 16\u201321 | year = 2008 | pmid =  18769411| pmc = | doi-access = free }}</ref> In discussing the name of the centre, Sanger (still alive when the centre was opened) told [[John Sulston]], the founding director, that the centre \"had better be good.\" Sulston commented, \"I rather wished I hadn\u2019t asked.\"<ref name=\"Interview with John Sulston\">{{cite web|last1=Sulston|first1=John|title=Interview with John Sulston|url=http://library.cshl.edu/oralhistory/interview/scientific-experience/molecular-biologists/sulston-frederick-sanger/|publisher=Cold Spring Harbor Laboratories digital archive|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Sequencing===\nThe Sanger Institute's sequencing staff handle millions of [[DNA]] samples each week.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} The Institute \"capitalises on leading-edge technologies to answer questions unanswerable only a few years ago\".<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.sanger.ac.uk/resources/technologies/sequencing.html|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - Sequencing|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> The advances in technology allow the Sanger Institute to carry out sequencing  of the genomes of individual humans, [[vertebrate]] [[species]] and [[pathogens]], at an ever-increasing pace and reducing cost. The Institute has more than 100 ongoing pathogen sequencing projects.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/projects/pathogengenomics/|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - Pathogen genomics|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> The output of the Sanger Institute is around 10 billion [[base pair|bases]] of raw sequence data per day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellcome.ac.uk/News/2008/Features/WTX052290.htm|author=Jones, I|title=Feature: Highly cited|publisher=Wellcome Trust|accessdate=2009-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Scientific resources===\n{{Update|section|date=April 2015}}\n[[Bioinformatic]] databases resources are one of the outcomes of research programmes that the Sanger Institute is involved in. Those hosted by the Sanger Institute include:\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[COSMIC cancer database|COSMIC]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 25355519| pmc = 4383913| year = 2015| last1 = Forbes| first1 = S. A.| title = COSMIC: Exploring the world's knowledge of somatic mutations in human cancer| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 43| issue = Database issue| pages = D805\u201311| last2 = Beare| first2 = D| last3 = Gunasekaran| first3 = P| last4 = Leung| first4 = K| last5 = Bindal| first5 = N| last6 = Boutselakis| first6 = H| last7 = Ding| first7 = M| last8 = Bamford| first8 = S| last9 = Cole| first9 = C| last10 = Ward| first10 = S| last11 = Kok| first11 = C. Y.| last12 = Jia| first12 = M| last13 = De| first13 = T| last14 = Teague| first14 = J. W.| last15 = Stratton| first15 = M. R. | authorlink15 = Michael Stratton| last16 = McDermott| first16 = U| last17 = Campbell| first17 = P. J.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gku1075}} {{open access}}</ref> a catalogue of [[Somatic (biology)|somatic]] mutations in cancer\n* [[DECIPHER]], a database of chromosomal imbalance and [[phenotype]] in humans, using Ensembl resources<ref name=decipher>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24150940| pmc = 3965078| year = 2014| last1 = Bragin| first1 = E| title = DECIPHER: Database for the interpretation of phenotype-linked plausibly pathogenic sequence and copy-number variation| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D993\u2013D1000| last2 = Chatzimichali| first2 = E. A.| last3 = Wright| first3 = C. F.| last4 = Hurles| first4 = M. E.| last5 = Firth| first5 = H. V.| last6 = Bevan| first6 = A. P.| last7 = Swaminathan| first7 = G. J.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt937}}</ref>\n* [[Ensembl]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 25352552| year = 2015| last1 = Cunningham| first1 = F| title = Ensembl 2015| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 43| issue = Database issue| pages = D662\u20139| last2 = Amode| first2 = M. R.| last3 = Barrell| first3 = D| last4 = Beal| first4 = K| last5 = Billis| first5 = K| last6 = Brent| first6 = S| last7 = Carvalho-Silva| first7 = D| last8 = Clapham| first8 = P| last9 = Coates| first9 = G| last10 = Fitzgerald| first10 = S| last11 = Gil| first11 = L| last12 = Gir\u00f3n| first12 = C. G.| last13 = Gordon| first13 = L| last14 = Hourlier| first14 = T| last15 = Hunt| first15 = S. E.| last16 = Janacek| first16 = S. H.| last17 = Johnson| first17 = N| last18 = Juettemann| first18 = T| last19 = K\u00e4h\u00e4ri| first19 = A. K.| last20 = Keenan| first20 = S| last21 = Martin| first21 = F. J.| last22 = Maurel| first22 = T| last23 = McLaren| first23 = W| last24 = Murphy| first24 = D. N.| last25 = Nag| first25 = R| last26 = Overduin| first26 = B| last27 = Parker| first27 = A| last28 = Patricio| first28 = M| last29 = Perry| first29 = E| last30 = Pignatelli| first30 = M| display-authors = 29| doi = 10.1093/nar/gku1010 | pmc=4383879}}</ref> a genome browser co-hosted by the European Bioinformatics Institute.\n* GeneDB,<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 22116062| pmc = 3245030| year = 2012| last1 = Logan-Klumpler| first1 = F. J.| title = GeneDB--an annotation database for pathogens| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 40| issue = Database issue| pages = D98\u2013108| last2 = De Silva| first2 = N| last3 = Boehme| first3 = U| last4 = Rogers| first4 = M. B.| last5 = Velarde| first5 = G| last6 = McQuillan| first6 = J. A.| last7 = Carver| first7 = T| last8 = Aslett| first8 = M| last9 = Olsen| first9 = C| last10 = Subramanian| first10 = S| last11 = Phan| first11 = I| last12 = Farris| first12 = C| last13 = Mitra| first13 = S| last14 = Ramasamy| first14 = G| last15 = Wang| first15 = H| last16 = Tivey| first16 = A| last17 = Jackson| first17 = A| last18 = Houston| first18 = R| last19 = Parkhill| first19 = J| last20 = Holden| first20 = M| last21 = Harb| first21 = O. S.| last22 = Brunk| first22 = B. P.| last23 = Myler| first23 = P. J.| last24 = Roos| first24 = D| last25 = Carrington| first25 = M| last26 = Smith| first26 = D. F.| last27 = Hertz-Fowler| first27 = C| last28 = Berriman| first28 = M| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkr1032}}</ref> a [[pathogen]] sequence database\n* [[Mouse Genetics Project]], including a database of standardised phenotypic analysis for many hundreds of mutant mice.\n* [[Vertebrate and Genome Annotation Project|Vega]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 18003653| pmc = 2238886| year = 2008| last1 = Wilming| first1 = L. G.| title = The vertebrate genome annotation (Vega) database| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 36| issue = Database issue| pages = D753\u201360| last2 = Gilbert| first2 = J. G.| last3 = Howe| first3 = K| last4 = Trevanion| first4 = S| last5 = Hubbard| first5 = T| last6 = Harrow| first6 = J. L.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkm987}}</ref> a vertebrate genome annotation resource\n{{colend}}\n\nSeveral databases were initiated at the Sanger Institute but are now hosted elsewhere:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[MEROPS]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24157837| pmc = 3964991| year = 2014| last1 = Rawlings| first1 = N. D.| title = MEROPS: The database of proteolytic enzymes, their substrates and inhibitors| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D503\u20139| last2 = Waller| first2 = M| last3 = Barrett| first3 = A. J.| last4 = Bateman| first4 = A| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt953}}</ref> a [[peptidase]] database\n* [[Pfam]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24288371| pmc = 3965110| year = 2014| last1 = Finn| first1 = R. D.| title = Pfam: The protein families database| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D222\u201330| last2 = Bateman| first2 = A | authorlink2 = Alex Bateman| last3 = Clements| first3 = J| last4 = Coggill| first4 = P| last5 = Eberhardt| first5 = R. Y.| last6 = Eddy| first6 = S. R. | authorlink6 = Sean Eddy| last7 = Heger| first7 = A| last8 = Hetherington| first8 = K| last9 = Holm| first9 = L| last10 = Mistry| first10 = J| last11 = Sonnhammer| first11 = E. L.| last12 = Tate| first12 = J| last13 = Punta| first13 = M| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt1223}} {{open access}}</ref> a [[protein family]] database\n* [[Rfam]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 25392425| pmc = 4383904| year = 2015| last1 = Nawrocki| first1 = E. P.| title = Rfam 12.0: Updates to the RNA families database| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 43| issue = Database issue| pages = D130\u20137| last2 = Burge| first2 = S. W.| last3 = Bateman| first3 = A| last4 = Daub| first4 = J| last5 = Eberhardt| first5 = R. Y.| last6 = Eddy| first6 = S. R.| last7 = Floden| first7 = E. W.| last8 = Gardner| first8 = P. P.| last9 = Jones| first9 = T. A.| last10 = Tate| first10 = J| last11 = Finn| first11 = R. D.| doi = 10.1093/nar/gku1063}}</ref> an [[RNA]] family database\n* [[TreeFam]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24194607| pmc = 3965059| year = 2014| last1 = Schreiber| first1 = F| title = Tree ''Fam'' v9: A new website, more species and orthology-on-the-fly| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D922\u20135| last2 = Patricio| first2 = M| last3 = Muffato| first3 = M| last4 = Pignatelli| first4 = M| last5 = Bateman| first5 = A| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt1055}}</ref> a database of [[phylogenetic]] trees for animal genes\n* [[WormBase]],<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 24194605| pmc = 3965043| year = 2014| last1 = Harris| first1 = T. W.| title = Worm ''Base'' 2014: New views of curated biology| journal = Nucleic Acids Research| volume = 42| issue = Database issue| pages = D789\u201393| last2 = Baran| first2 = J| last3 = Bieri| first3 = T| last4 = Cabunoc| first4 = A| last5 = Chan| first5 = J| last6 = Chen| first6 = W. J.| last7 = Davis| first7 = P| last8 = Done| first8 = J| last9 = Grove| first9 = C| last10 = Howe| first10 = K| last11 = Kishore| first11 = R| last12 = Lee| first12 = R| last13 = Li| first13 = Y| last14 = Muller| first14 = H. M.| last15 = Nakamura| first15 = C| last16 = Ozersky| first16 = P| last17 = Paulini| first17 = M| last18 = Raciti| first18 = D| last19 = Schindelman| first19 = G| last20 = Tuli| first20 = M. A.| last21 = Van Auken| first21 = K| last22 = Wang| first22 = D| last23 = Wang| first23 = X| last24 = Williams| first24 = G| last25 = Wong| first25 = J. D.| last26 = Yook| first26 = K| last27 = Schedl| first27 = T| last28 = Hodgkin| first28 = J| last29 = Berriman| first29 = M| last30 = Kersey| first30 = P| display-authors = 29| doi = 10.1093/nar/gkt1063}}</ref> a database on the biology and sequence of the [[model organism]] ''[[Caenorhabditis elegans|C. elegans]]'' and other related Nematodes.\n* [[WormBase ParaSite]], a database for the genomics for parasitic [[helminths]] (both Nematodes and Platyhelminthes).\n{{colend}}\n\n==Research==\n[[File:Hinxton hall.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Morgan Building (right), part of the Sanger Institute]]\n\nScientific research at the Sanger Institute is organised into five Scientific Programmes, each defining a major area of research with a particular biological, disease or analytic focus. The current Programmes at the Sanger Institute are Cancer, Ageing and Somatic Mutation, Cellular Genetics, Human Genetics, Parasites and Microbes and Tree of Life. Studies from all programmes provide insights into human, pathogen, cellular evolution, the phenotypic and hence biological consequences of genome variation and the processes which cause mutations.\n\n===Cancer, Ageing and Somatic Mutation Programme===\nProvides leadership in data aggregation and informatics innovation, develops high-throughput cellular models of cancer for genome-wide functional screens and drug testing, and explores somatic mutation's role in clonal evolution, ageing and development. This Programme includes the [[Cancer Genome Project]].\n\n===Cellular Genetics Programme===\nExplores human gene function by studying the impact of genome variation on cell biology. Large-scale systematic screens are used to discover the impact of naturally occurring and engineered genome mutations in human induced pluripotent cells (hIPSCs), their differentiated derivatives and other cell types. It is one of the founder programmes driving the creation and organisation of the international [[Human Cell Atlas]] initiative.\n\n===Human Genetics Programme===\nThe Institute's research in [[human genetics]] focuses on the characterisation of [[human genetic variation]] in health and disease. Aside from the Institute's contribution to the [[Human Genome Project]], researchers at the Sanger Institute have made contributions in various research areas relating to disease, population comparative and [[Extended evolutionary synthesis|evolutionary genetics]]. In January 2008, the launch of the [[1000 Genomes Project]], a collaboration with scientists around the globe, signalled an effort to sequence the genomes of 1000 individuals in order to create the \"most detailed map of human genetic variation to support disease studies\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1000genomes.org/page.php|title=1000 Genomes: A Deep Catalog of Human Genetic Variation|publisher=1000 Genomes Project|accessdate=2008-12-22}}</ref> The data from the pilot projects was made freely available in public databases in June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/press/2010/100621.html|title=1000 Genomes Project releases data from pilot projects on path to providing database for 2,500 human genomes|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> In 2010, the Sanger Institute announced its participation in the UK10K project,<ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 24424120\n| pmc = 4026295\n| year = 2014\n| last1 = Kaye\n| first1 = J\n| title = Managing clinically significant findings in research: The UK10K example\n| journal = European Journal of Human Genetics\n| volume = 22\n| issue = 9\n| pages = 1100\u20134\n| last2 = Hurles\n| first2 = M\n| last3 = Griffin\n| first3 = H\n| last4 = Grewal\n| first4 = J\n| last5 = Bobrow\n| first5 = M | authorlink5 = Martin Bobrow\n| last6 = Timpson\n| first6 = N\n| last7 = Smee\n| first7 = C\n| last8 = Bolton\n| first8 = P\n| last9 = Durbin\n| first9 = R | authorlink9 = Richard M. Durbin\n| last10 = Dyke\n| first10 = S\n| last11 = Fitzpatrick\n| first11 = D\n| last12 = Kennedy\n| first12 = K\n| last13 = Kent\n| first13 = A\n| last14 = Muddyman\n| first14 = D\n| last15 = Muntoni\n| first15 = F\n| last16 = Raymond\n| first16 = L. F.\n| last17 = Semple\n| first17 = R\n| last18 = Spector\n| first18 = T\n| last19 = Uk\n| first19 = 10K\n| doi = 10.1038/ejhg.2013.290\n}} {{open access}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 24229443\n| pmc = 3978569\n| year = 2013\n| last1 = Muddyman\n| first1 = D\n| title = Implementing a successful data-management framework: The UK10K managed access model\n| journal = Genome Medicine\n| volume = 5\n| issue = 11\n| pages = 100\n| last2 = Smee\n| first2 = C\n| last3 = Griffin\n| first3 = H\n| last4 = Kaye\n| first4 = J\n| doi = 10.1186/gm504\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/press/2010/100624-uk10k.html|title=Wellcome Trust launches study of 10,000 human genomes in UK|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> which will sequence the genomes of 10,000 individuals to identify rare genetic variants and their effects on human health. The Sanger Institute is also part of the [[International Cancer Genome Consortium]], an international effort to describe different cancer [[tumour]] types.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icgc.org/|title=International Cancer Genome Consortium Homepage|publisher=International Cancer Genome Consortium|accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref> It is also part of the [[GENCODE]] and [[ENCODE]] research programmes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/resources/databases/encode//|title=Wellcome Sanger Institute - ENCODE and GENCODE|accessdate=2010-06-28}}</ref> to create an encyclopaedia of DNA elements.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe Programme applies genomics to population-scale studies to identify the causal variants and pathways involved in human disease and their effects on cell biology. It also models developmental disorders to explore which physical aspects might be reversible.\n\n===Pathogens and Microbes Programme===\nInvestigates the common underpinning mechanisms of evolution, infection and resistance to therapy into bolster understanding of [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es and [[parasitism|parasites]], with a particular interest in [[malaria]]. It also explores the effects of genome variation on the biology of [[host (biology)|host]]-[[pathogen]] interactions, in particular host response to infection and the role of microiotia in health and disease. All the genomes after sequencing are made available at the web-based onsite-maintained database, GeneDB.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n=== Tree of Life Programme ===\nThe Tree of Life Programme was created in 2019 to investigate the diversity of complex organisms found in the UK through sequencing and cellular technologies. It also compares and contrasts species' genome sequences to unlock insights into evolution and conservation. This Programme will play a leading role in the Darwin Tree of Life Project, a UK-wide initiative to sequence the genomes of all 66,000 complex species (eukaryotes) in the British Isles.\n\n===Collaborations===\nMuch of the Sanger Institute's research is carried out in partnership with the wider [[scientific community]]; over 90 percent of the Institute's research papers involve collaborations with other organisations.<ref>Figure based on data for 2008 retrieved from SCOPUS website</ref> Significant collaborations include:\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[1000 Genomes Project]]\n* [[GENCODE]] and [[ENCODE]] (ENCyclopedia Of DNA Elements)\n* [[International Cancer Genome Consortium]]\n* [[International HapMap Project]]<ref>{{Cite journal| last1 = - | first1 = -| last2 = Gibbs | first2 = R. A. | last3 = Belmont | first3 = J. W. | last4 = Hardenbol | first4 = P. | last5 = Willis | first5 = T. D. | last6 = Yu | first6 = F. | last7 = Yang | first7 = H. | last8 = Ch'Ang | first8 = L. Y. | last9 = Huang | first9 = W. | doi = 10.1038/nature02168| last10 = Liu | first10 = B.| last11 = Shen | first11 = Y.| last12 = Tam | first12 = P. K. H.| last13 = Tsui | first13 = L. C.| last14 = Waye | first14 = M. M. Y.| last15 = Wong | first15 = J. T. F.| last16 = Zeng | first16 = C.| last17 = Zhang | first17 = Q.| last18 = Chee | first18 = M. S.| last19 = Galver | first19 = L. M.| last20 = Kruglyak | first20 = S.| last21 = Murray | first21 = S. S.| last22 = Oliphant | first22 = A. R.| last23 = Montpetit | first23 = A.| last24 = Hudson | first24 = T. J.| last25 = Chagnon | first25 = F.| last26 = Ferretti | first26 = V.| last27 = Leboeuf | first27 = M.| last28 = Phillips | first28 = M. S.| last29 = Verner | first29 = A.| last30 = Kwok | first30 = P. Y. | title = The International HapMap Project | journal = Nature | volume = 426 | issue = 6968 | pages = 789\u2013796 | year = 2003 | pmid = 14685227 | pmc = | url = https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/62838/1/nature02168.pdf|hdl = 2027.42/62838| bibcode = 2003Natur.426..789G| displayauthors = 29}}</ref>\n* [[International Knockout Mouse Consortium]]\n* [[International Mouse Phenotyping Consortium]]\n* SNP ([[Single nucleotide polymorphism]]) Consortium\n* The Copy Number Variation Project<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/humgen/cnv/|title=Programmes - Wellcome Sanger Institute|first=www-core|last=(webteam)|date=|website=www.sanger.ac.uk|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref> \n* The [[genome sequencing]] of ''[[Schizosaccharomyces pombe|S. pombe]]'', ''[[Caenorhabditis elegans|C. elegans]]'', [[mouse]] and the [[Malaria]] parasite.\n* The [[Human Genome Project]]\n* The UK 10,000 Genomes Project (UK10K)<ref>[http://www.uk10k.org/ UK10K] (the UK 10,000 Genomes Project)</ref> \n* [[Wellcome Trust]] - [[Department of Biotechnology]], [[India]] Alliance<ref>http://www.wellcomedbt.org/Mini_symposium_final_poster_schedule.pdf</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n===Public engagement===\n[[File:Sanger Institute outreach DNA bracelets.jpg|thumb|Children at a public outreach event thread bracelets in four colours to spell out a DNA sequence.]]\nThe Sanger Institute has a programme of [[public engagement]] activity. The programme aims to make complex biomedical research accessible to a range of audiences including school students and their teachers, and local community members.\n\nThe Communication and Public Engagement programme aims to \"encourage informed discussion about issues relevant to Sanger Institute research\"<ref name=\"Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute\" /> and \"foster a community of researchers who can engage effectively with different audiences\".<ref name=\"Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/Teams/Team104/|title=Team 104: Communication and Public Engagement Programme|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2009-01-12}}</ref> The Institute hosts visits for more than 1,500 students, teachers and community groups per year. Visitors may meet scientific staff, tour the Institute and its facilities, and participate in ethical debates and activities. The programme also offers professional development sessions for teachers of [[GCSE]] and post 16 science through the national network of [[Science Learning Centres]], and by hosting visits for groups interested in updating their knowledge in contemporary genetics. [[Videoconferencing]] into the Sanger Institute is also offered for Science Learning Centres, Science Centres and schools.\n\nScientific and public engagement staff also collaborate on and contribute to national projects such as the UK's ''InsideDNA''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidedna.org.uk/content/|title=InsideDNA|author=|date=|website=insidedna.org.uk|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>  traveling exhibition and the ''Who am I?'' gallery at [[Science Museum (London)|The Science Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/|title=Home - Science Museum|author=|date=|website=Science Museum|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref> They also participate in public events such as the Cambridge Science Festival.\n\n===Graduate training===\nThe Institute operates two PhD training programmes: a four-year course for basic science graduates, and a three-year course for clinicians. The four-year course requires students to rotate around three different laboratories in order to broaden their scientific horizons before choosing a PhD project. Each student is required to choose at least one experimental and one informatics-based rotation project.<ref>\n{{cite web| url        = http://www.sanger.ac.uk/careers/phd/| title      = Wellcome Sanger Institute PhD Programmes| publisher  = Wellcome Sanger Institute| accessdate = 2009-11-13}}</ref> Institute houses approximately 50 pre-doctoral students, all of whom are registered at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407104250/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/publications/theses.html|title=Sanger PhD and MPhil theses|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/publications/theses.html|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Officers==\nAccording to Companies House the five officers of the parent company Genome Research Limited are Henry Parkinson, Kay Elizabeth Davies, Rolf Dieter Heuer, James Cuthbert Smith, David Lindsay Willetts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/02742969/officers |title=GENOME RESEARCH LIMITED - Officers}}</ref> According to the Sanger website Henry Parkinson is head of legal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sanger.ac.uk/people/directory/parkinson-henry}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n\n{{As of|2015}} the Sanger employs around 900 people, and is led by [[Michael Stratton]]. Notable scientific staff, [[Faculty (academic staff)|faculty]] and alumni are listed below:\n\n===Academic faculty===\n{{As of|2019}} a faculty of 32 scientists lead [[hypothesis]]-driven research, seeking answers to biomedical questions.<ref name=faculty>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316171820/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/|title=Sanger Faculty|archivedate=2015-03-16}}</ref> Among others, these include [[Dominic Kwiatkowski]], [[Nicole Soranzo]], [[Michael Stratton]], [[Sarah Teichmann]] and [[Matthew Hurles]]. The institute also has a number of Associate Faculty members, International Fellows and Honorary Faculty. These include [[Adrian Bird]], [[Ewan Birney]], [[Chris Ponting]], [[Fiona Powrie]], [[Stephen O'Rahilly]] and [[Wolf Reik]], among others.\n\n===Scientific advisory board===\n\nThe Sanger [[Board of directors|Board of Management]] are guided by the scientific [[advisory board]]<ref name=sab>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407104047/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/people/advisory.html|title=Sanger Advisory Board|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/people/advisory.html|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref> whose members include Professor [[David Altshuler (physician)|David Altshuler]], Professor [[Anton Berns]], Professor [[David J. Lipman]], Professor Kevin Marsh and Professor Sir [[Paul Nurse]].\n\n===Alumni===\nPrevious faculty members at the Sanger include:<ref name=alumni>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407104218/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/previousfaculty/|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/previousfaculty/|title=Previous faculty at the Sanger|archivedate=2015-04-07}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n*[[Alex Bateman]], [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory|EMBL]]-[[European Bioinformatics Institute|EBI]]<ref name=wiki>{{Cite journal | last1 = Logan | first1 = D. W. | last2 = Sandal | first2 = M. | last3 = Gardner | first3 = P. P. | authorlink3  =| last4 = Manske | first4 = M. | authorlink4 = Magnus Manske| last5 = Bateman | first5 = A. | authorlink5 =  Alex Bateman| title = Ten Simple Rules for Editing Wikipedia | doi = 10.1371/journal.pcbi.1000941 | journal = [[PLOS Computational Biology]] | volume = 6 | issue = 9 | pages = e1000941 | year = 2010 | pmid =  20941386| pmc =2947980 | bibcode = 2010PLSCB...6E0941L }} {{open access}}</ref>\n* [[Tim Hubbard]], Professor at [[King's College London]]\n* [[Leena Peltonen-Palotie]] (1952 \u2013  2010)<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = van Ommen | first1 = Gertjan| title = Obituary: Leena Peltonen-Palotie (1952\u20132010) A visionary in medical genetics.| doi = 10.1038/464992a | journal = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]| volume = 464 | issue = 7291 | pages = 992 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20393553| pmc = | title-link = Leena Peltonen-Palotie}}</ref>\n* [[Julian Rayner]] \n* [[Eleftheria Zeggini]]\n* [[Richard M. Durbin|Richard Durbin]] FRS\n\n{{colend}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:EBI and Sanger Center, Genome campus, Cambridgeshire.jpg|350px|right|thumb|The Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute was established in 1992, funded by the [[Wellcome Trust]] and the UK's [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]]]]\n\n===Management ===\n[[John E. Sulston]] was the founding Director of the Sanger Institute. Sulston was instrumental in the choice of the Hinxton site for the Institute and remained there as Director until the announcement of the completion of the draft human genome in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genome.gov/10001457|title=International Human Genome Sequencing Consortium Announces \"Working Draft\" of Human Genome|publisher=National Human Genome Research Institute|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref> Sulston graduated from the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1963 and completed his PhD on the chemical synthesis of DNA in 1966.<ref>{{cite book|author=Sulston J, Ferry G|title=The Common Thread: A story of Science, Politics, Ethics, and the Human Genome|year=2002|publisher=The Joseph Henry Press|page=18}}</ref> He shared the 2002 [[Nobel Prize]] in Physiology or Medicine with [[Robert Horvitz]] and [[Sydney Brenner]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/2002/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine 2002|publisher=Nobel Prize|accessdate=2009-01-07}}</ref> two years after standing down as Director of the Institute.\n\nIn 2000, [[Allan Bradley]] left his appointment as Professor at the [[Baylor College of Medicine]], in the US, to take up the position as Director of the Sanger Institute. Bradley wanted to build on the achievements made by the Sanger Institute in the Human Genome Project by \"concentrating on gene function, cancer genomics, and the genomes of model organisms such as the mouse and the zebrafish\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genomebiology.com/researchnews/default.asp?arx_id=gb-spotlight-20011106-02 |title=Sanger Institute looks to the future |publisher=Genome Biology |accessdate=2008-12-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040119195438/http://genomebiology.com/researchnews/default.asp?arx_id=gb-spotlight-20011106-02 |archivedate=January 19, 2004 }}</ref> Bradley received his BA, MA and PhD in Genetics from the University of Cambridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/Teams/faculty/bradley/|title=Professor Allan Bradley|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|archivedate=2015-04-07|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407061817/http://www.sanger.ac.uk/research/faculty/abradley/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 10839511| year = 2000| last1 = Gura| first1 = T| title = Changing of the guard: Allan Bradley is to head the Sanger Centre, a powerhouse of the Human Genome Project| journal = Nature| volume = 405| issue = 6785| pages = 389| doi = 10.1038/35013238}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 11606985| year = 2001| last1 = Adam| first1 = D| title = Sanger Centre welcomes gene funds with a new name| journal = Nature| volume = 413| issue = 6857| pages = 660| doi = 10.1038/35099707| bibcode = 2001Natur.413R.660A| doi-access = free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 10830929| year = 2000| last1 = Dickson| first1 = D| title = Geneticist from Baylor named as new head of UK's Sanger Centre| journal = Nature| volume = 405| issue = 6784| pages = 264| doi = 10.1038/35012766| doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Bradley stepped down from his leadership role to form a [[startup company]], but remains on the faculty of the Institute as Director Emeritus. [[Michael Stratton|Mike Stratton]], who is a leader of the [[Cancer Genome Project]] and the [[International Cancer Genome Consortium]], was appointed Director of the Sanger Institute in May of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/about/press/2010/100517.html |title=Professor Mike Stratton appointed new Director|publisher=Wellcome Sanger Institute|accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref>\n\n===Human Genome Project===\nThe Sanger Institute was opened in 1993, three years after the inception of the [[Human Genome Project]], and went on to make the largest single contribution to the gold standard sequence of the [[human genome]], published in 2004.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Human Genome Sequencing Consortium|title=Finishing the euchromatic sequence of the human genome|journal=Nature|year=2004|volume=431|pages=931\u2013945|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v431/n7011/index.html|doi=10.1038/nature03001|pmid=15496913|issue=7011|bibcode=2004Natur.431..931H|doi-access=free}}</ref> The Institute was engaged in collaborations to sequence 8 of the 23 human pairs of [[chromosomes]] ([[chromosome 1|1]], [[chromosome 6|6]], [[chromosome 9|9]], [[chromosome 10|10]], [[chromosome 13|13]], [[chromosome 20|20]], [[chromosome 22|22]], and [[X chromosome|X]]).<ref>{{cite journal|author=Pennisi E|title=Reaching Their Goal Early, Sequencing Labs Celebrate|journal=Science|year=2003|volume=300|page=409|doi=10.1126/science.300.5618.409|pmid=12702850|issue=5618}}</ref> Since the publishing of the human genome, research carried out at the Institute has developed beyond sequencing of organisms into various biomedical research areas, including studies into diseases such as cancer, malaria and diabetes.\n\n==Controversy==\nIn August 2018 it was reported that an investigation was under way into allegations of bullying of staff and gender discrimination made against senior management of the [[Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute]], including the director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2018/aug/29/wellcome-sanger-institute-bosses-accused-bullying-staff|title=Bosses at leading UK science institute accused of bullying staff|last=Marsh|first=Sarah|last2=Devlin|first2=Hannah|date=2018-08-29|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-29}}</ref> The investigation, carried out by the barrister Thomas Kibling from [[Matrix Chambers]], concluded in October 2018 and cleared Stratton of any wrongdoing, while listing areas for improvement in the workings of the Sanger Institute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanger.ac.uk/news/view/result-independent-investigation-whistleblowing-allegations-released |title=Result of independent investigation into whistleblowing allegations released |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2018-10-31|website=Sanger Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanger.ac.uk/sites/default/files/Oct2018/Thomas_Kibling_Investigatory_Report_-_Introduction_and_Executive_Summary.pdf |title=Thomas Kibling's Investigatory Report |author=Thomas Kibling |date=2018-10-31|website=Sanger Institute|language=en|access-date=2018-10-31}}</ref> The findings and the independence of the investigation were disputed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-018-07339-4 |title=Sanger whistle-blowers dispute findings that cleared management of bullying |date=2018-11-08}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019 it was reported that the institute had manufactured a medical tool with the intent of monetising it despite not having ethical nor legal approval to do so and having been made aware by [[Stellenbosch University]] and internal whistleblowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/genetics-lab-told-to-hand-back-african-tribes-dna-83xqls5sh |title=Genetics lab told to hand back African tribes' DNA}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{URL|sanger.ac.uk}}\n\n{{bioinformatics}}\n{{Wellcome Trust}}\n{{coord|52|05|N|0|11|E|region:GB_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Partner institutions of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Genetic engineering in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Genetics or genomics research institutions]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:South Cambridgeshire District]]\n[[Category:Wellcome Trust]]\n", "name_user": "Statjak", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wellcome_Sanger_Institute"}
{"title_page": "Navicat", "text_new": "{{Third-party|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox Software\n| name                   = Navicat\n| logo                   = Navicat_Premium_v12.png\n| logo size              = 200px\n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = PremiumSoft Navicat Premium v.9.0 running on [[Windows 7]]\n| author                 = PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd.\n| developer              = PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd.\n| latest_release_version = <!-- If you update this, remember to also update [[Comparison of database tools]]--> 15.0.13\n| latest_release_date    = 2020-04-15\n| released               = 2002\n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| language               = [[#Supported platforms and languages|Multilingual]]\n| genre                  = [[SQL]] [[Database management system|database management and development system]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary Software|Proprietary]] / [[Shareware]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://www.navicat.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Navicat''' is a series of graphical [[database management]] and development software produced by PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd. for [[MySQL]], [[MariaDB]], [[MongoDB]], [[Oracle Database|Oracle]], [[SQLite]], [[PostgreSQL]] and [[Microsoft SQL Server]]. It has an Explorer-like graphical user interface and supports multiple [[database connection]]s for local and remote databases. Its design is made to meet the needs of a variety of audiences, from database administrators and programmers to various businesses/companies that serve clients and share information with partners.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=ONLamp.com|title=Navicat Review|date=2004-12-22|author=Blane Warrene|url=http://onlamp.com/pub/a/onlamp/2004/12/22/navicat.html|accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref><ref name=\"lasplash.com\">{{cite web|publisher=Splash Magazines|title=Navicat MySQL GUI Review|author=Zachary Richley|url=http://www.lasplash.com/publish/Software_Reviews_and_News_130/navicat_mysql_gui_review.php|accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe initial version of Navicat was developed in 2001. The main target of the initial version was to simplify the management of [[MySQL]] installations. In 2008, Navicat for MySQL  was the winner of the Hong Kong ICT 2008 ''Award of the Year'', ''Best Business Grand Award'' and ''Best Business (Product) Gold Award''.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Hong Kong Computer Society|title=Best Business Grand Award: PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd. Navicat for MySQL|date=2008|url=http://www.hkictawards.hk/news.asp?menuid=10034&supmenuid=10022|accessdate=2014-12-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141123233446/http://www.hkictawards.hk/news.asp?menuid=10034&supmenuid=10022|archivedate=2014-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==Supported platforms and languages==\nNavicat is a cross-platform tool and works on [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Mac OS X]] and [[Linux]] platforms. Upon purchase, users are able to select a language for the software from eleven available languages: English, French, German, Spanish, Japanese, Polish, Russian, Portuguese, Korean, Simplified Chinese and Traditional Chinese.\n\nIt supports [[Linux]] platform via bundled [[Wine]].\n\n==Versions==\n\n===Standalone versions===\nOfficially released in March 2002, the [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] version of Navicat for [[MySQL]] became the first product offered to the public by PremiumSoft. Subsequently, the company released two additional versions of Navicat for MySQL on the [[Mac OS X]] and [[Linux]] operating system in June and October 2003 respectively. In November 2013, added the support of MariaDB.<ref name=\"Navicat MySQL notes\">{{cite web|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for MySQL release notes|date=2002{{ndash}}14|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-mysql-release-note|accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Techmixer|title=NaviCat MySQL \u2013 MySQL Database Management Tools For Windows|date=2009|url=http://www.techmixer.com/navicat-mysql-mysql-database-management-tools-for-windows}}</ref> PremiumSoft continued to expand their Navicat series by releasing Navicat for [[PostgreSQL]] for Windows in October 2005 and then for Mac OS X in June 2006. The Linux version of Navicat for PostgreSQL would not be released until 3 years later in August 2009.<ref name=\"Navicat PostgreSQL notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for PostgreSQL release notes|date=2008{{ndash}}14|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-postgresql-release-note}}</ref> In August 2008 Navicat decided to further continue their product line and branch out into the [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] community, creating Navicat for Oracle for Windows and Mac. In August of the following year they followed up with a version for the Linux Platform.<ref name=\"Navicat Oracle notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for Oracle release notes|date=2008{{ndash}}14|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-oracle-release-note}}</ref> The Oracle version of Navicat supports most of the latest Oracle objects features including Directory, Tablespace, Synonym, Materialized View, Trigger, Sequence, and Type, etc.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for Oracle overview|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-oracle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Techmixer|title=Navicat for Oracle \u2013 Oracle Administration Tools For Windows And Mac|url=http://www.techmixer.com/navicat-for-oracle-windows-oracle-administration-tools}}</ref> Navicat for [[SQLite]] was released for Windows and Mac OS X simultaneously in April 2009, and the Linux version soon followed two months later in June of the same year.<ref name=\"Navicat SQLite notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQLite release notes|date=2010{{ndash}}14|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-sqlite-release-note}}</ref> In April 2010, Navicat Premium began including Navicat for SQLite starting from version 9 to expand the usability of Navicat Premium.<ref name=\"Navicat Premium notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Premium release notes|date=2009{{ndash}}14|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/products/navicat-premium-release-note}}</ref> Navicat for SQL Server was released in November 2010 for the Windows platform and Mac OS X. Also at the release, the SQL server version was included in the Premium version of Navicat. In January 2011, support for [[SQL Azure]] was added.<ref name=\"Navicat for SQL Server notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQL server overview|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-sqlserver}}</ref> Navicat for MariaDB was released in November 2013 for Windows, Mac OS X and Linux. Also at the release, the MariaDB version was included in both Navicat Premium and Navicat for MySQL.\n\nIn 2018, Navicat started to support NoSQL databases. [[MongoDB]] is currently the newest addition to the list of server Navicat supports. The new line of product, called Navicat for MongoDB, was released in July 2018 for Windows, Mac OS X and Linux. It provides a native environment for MongoDB management and supports the extra features like MapReduce, GridFS Buckets. Also at the release, the MongoDB version was included in Navicat Premium.\n\n===Navicat Premium===\nIn 2009, PremiumSoft released Navicat Premium, a series of Navicat software that combines all previous Navicat versions into a single version and can connect to different database types including MySQL, Oracle, and PostgreSQL simultaneously, allowing users to do data migration between cross databases. Navicat Premium version also supports cross-platform administration, serving Windows, Mac OS X and Linux. In April 2010, version 9 of Navicat Premium was released, which added the connectivity of SQLite database to Navicat Premium, allowing Navicat Premium to connect to MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL and SQLite in a single application. In November 2010, support for Microsoft SQL Server was added. In January 2011, [[SQL Azure]] was included. In November 2013, added the support of MariaDB.<ref name=\"Navicat Premium notes\"/><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Techmixer|title=Navicat Premium \u2013 Cross Database Administrator Management Tool|url=http://www.techmixer.com/navicat-premium-cross-database-administrator-management-tool}}</ref> In July 2018, added the support of MongoDB.\n\n===Navicat Essentials===\nNavicat Essentials was officially released in November 2011. This is a simple Navicat version for commercial use. The Essentials editions of Navicat lack several features found in the Standard/Enterprise editions, including form view, record filtering, visual query building, data modeling and options for import, export and backup of data, etc.<ref name=\"Navicat Essentials features\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Essentials features|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-essentials}}</ref>\n\n===Navicat Data Modeler===\nNavicat Data Modeler Windows version was officially released in March 2012. Then, Mac OS X and Linux version were released in May 2012 and June 2012. This is a standalone product for developers to create data models for MySQL, SQL Server, Oracle, PostgreSQL and SQLite databases. Navicat Data Modeler allows users to visually design database structures, perform reverse/forward engineer process, import table structures from ODBC data sources, generate SQL files and print models to files, etc. In June 2015, added the support of MariaDB databases and several features such as Model Conversion, Physical/Logical/Conceptual model types and Navicat Cloud.\n\n===Navicat iOS===\nIn August 2014, PremiumSoft released a new product - Navicat iOS.<ref name=\"Navicat iOS\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat iOS|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/products}}</ref> It is a database administration tool developed for iOS with features included object viewer & designer, query builder & editor, Navicat Cloud,<ref name=\"Navicat Cloud\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Cloud|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/navicat-cloud}}</ref> server monitor, etc. MySQL was supported in the first release. Then, Navicat for PostgreSQL iOS version was released in January 2015. In September 2017, Navicat for MariaDB iOS version was released.\n\n===Navicat Cloud Collaboration===\nNavicat Cloud is a cloud service for users to synchronize their connection settings, queries, models and virtual groups with multiple platforms and devices. A user can share his project to others for collaborating on connection settings, queries and models.\n\n===Navicat Monitor===\nNavicat Monitor was officially released in April 2018. It is a safe, simple and agentless remote server monitoring tool and supports to monitor MySQL, MariaDB and cloud databases. Users can access Navicat Monitor from anywhere via a web browser. The main features of Navicat Monitor including real-time instance performance monitoring, alert notification, query analyzer, replications monitoring.\n\n==Features==\nNavicat's features include:\n\n* code snippet\n* visual query-builder\n* SSH and [[HTTP tunneling]]<ref name=\"lasplash.com\"/>\n* data and structure migration and synchronization\n* import and export and backup of data\n* report builder\n* data modeling\n* task scheduling and wizards tool\n\nThere are differences in the features available across operating systems.<ref name=\"features_MySQL\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for MySQL Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-mysql-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_MariaDB\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for MariaDB Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-mariadb-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_PostegreSQL\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for PostegreSQL Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-postgresql-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_Oracle\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for Oracle Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-oracle-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_SQLite\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQLite Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-sqlite-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_SQLServer\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQL Server Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-sqlserver-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_Premium\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Premium Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-premium-feature-matrix}}</ref>\n\nNavicat is also compatible with forks of [[MySQL]] such as [[Drizzle (database server)|Drizzle]], OurDelta, and Percona.<ref name=\"features_MySQL\"/>\n\nNavicat supports Cloud Databases like [[Amazon RDS]], [[Amazon Aurora]], [[Amazon Redshift]], [[SQL Azure]], [[Oracle Cloud]], [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]] and [[Alibaba Cloud]].<ref name=\"features_MySQL\"/><ref name=\"features_MariaDB\"/><ref name=\"features_PostegreSQL\"/><ref name=\"features_Oracle\"/><ref name=\"features_SQLServer\"/><ref name=\"features_Premium\"/>\n\n==Navicat Community==\nNavicat Community provides a flexible environment for Navicat users to post questions, share experiences and solutions. It includes forum discussions, blog articles, tutorial videos and Wiki FAQ.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Comparison of database tools]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.navicat.com/}}\n* [https://community.navicat.com/ Navicat Community]\n\n[[Category:MySQL]]\n[[Category:PostgreSQL]]\n[[Category:Database administration tools]]\n[[Category:Data modeling tools]]\n[[Category:Software companies of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Oracle database tools]]\n[[Category:Microsoft database software]]\n[[Category:MariaDB]]\n", "text_old": "{{Third-party|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox Software\n| name                   = Navicat\n| logo                   = Navicat_Premium_v12.png\n| logo size              = 200px\n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = PremiumSoft Navicat Premium v.9.0 running on [[Windows 7]]\n| author                 = PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd.\n| developer              = PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd.\n| latest_release_version = <!-- If you update this, remember to also update [[Comparison of database tools]]--> 12.1\n| latest_release_date    = 26 July 2018\n| released               = 2002\n| operating system       = [[Cross-platform]]\n| language               = [[#Supported platforms and languages|Multilingual]]\n| genre                  = [[SQL]] [[Database management system|database management and development system]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary Software|Proprietary]] / [[Shareware]]\n| website                = {{URL|https://www.navicat.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Navicat''' is a series of graphical [[database management]] and development software produced by PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd. for [[MySQL]], [[MariaDB]], [[MongoDB]], [[Oracle Database|Oracle]], [[SQLite]], [[PostgreSQL]] and [[Microsoft SQL Server]]. It has an Explorer-like graphical user interface and supports multiple [[database connection]]s for local and remote databases. Its design is made to meet the needs of a variety of audiences, from database administrators and programmers to various businesses/companies that serve clients and share information with partners.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=ONLamp.com|title=Navicat Review|date=2004-12-22|author=Blane Warrene|url=http://onlamp.com/pub/a/onlamp/2004/12/22/navicat.html|accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref><ref name=\"lasplash.com\">{{cite web|publisher=Splash Magazines|title=Navicat MySQL GUI Review|author=Zachary Richley|url=http://www.lasplash.com/publish/Software_Reviews_and_News_130/navicat_mysql_gui_review.php|accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe initial version of Navicat was developed in 2001. The main target of the initial version was to simplify the management of [[MySQL]] installations. In 2008, Navicat for MySQL  was the winner of the Hong Kong ICT 2008 ''Award of the Year'', ''Best Business Grand Award'' and ''Best Business (Product) Gold Award''.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Hong Kong Computer Society|title=Best Business Grand Award: PremiumSoft CyberTech Ltd. Navicat for MySQL|date=2008|url=http://www.hkictawards.hk/news.asp?menuid=10034&supmenuid=10022|accessdate=2014-12-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141123233446/http://www.hkictawards.hk/news.asp?menuid=10034&supmenuid=10022|archivedate=2014-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==Supported platforms and languages==\nNavicat is a cross-platform tool and works on [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Mac OS X]] and [[Linux]] platforms. Upon purchase, users are able to select a language for the software from eleven available languages: English, French, German, Spanish, Japanese, Polish, Russian, Portuguese, Korean, Simplified Chinese and Traditional Chinese.\n\nIt supports [[Linux]] platform via bundled [[Wine]].\n\n==Versions==\n\n===Standalone versions===\nOfficially released in March 2002, the [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] version of Navicat for [[MySQL]] became the first product offered to the public by PremiumSoft. Subsequently, the company released two additional versions of Navicat for MySQL on the [[Mac OS X]] and [[Linux]] operating system in June and October 2003 respectively. In November 2013, added the support of MariaDB.<ref name=\"Navicat MySQL notes\">{{cite web|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for MySQL release notes|date=2002{{ndash}}14|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-mysql-release-note|accessdate=2014-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Techmixer|title=NaviCat MySQL \u2013 MySQL Database Management Tools For Windows|date=2009|url=http://www.techmixer.com/navicat-mysql-mysql-database-management-tools-for-windows}}</ref> PremiumSoft continued to expand their Navicat series by releasing Navicat for [[PostgreSQL]] for Windows in October 2005 and then for Mac OS X in June 2006. The Linux version of Navicat for PostgreSQL would not be released until 3 years later in August 2009.<ref name=\"Navicat PostgreSQL notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for PostgreSQL release notes|date=2008{{ndash}}14|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-postgresql-release-note}}</ref> In August 2008 Navicat decided to further continue their product line and branch out into the [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] community, creating Navicat for Oracle for Windows and Mac. In August of the following year they followed up with a version for the Linux Platform.<ref name=\"Navicat Oracle notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for Oracle release notes|date=2008{{ndash}}14|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-oracle-release-note}}</ref> The Oracle version of Navicat supports most of the latest Oracle objects features including Directory, Tablespace, Synonym, Materialized View, Trigger, Sequence, and Type, etc.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for Oracle overview|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-oracle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Techmixer|title=Navicat for Oracle \u2013 Oracle Administration Tools For Windows And Mac|url=http://www.techmixer.com/navicat-for-oracle-windows-oracle-administration-tools}}</ref> Navicat for [[SQLite]] was released for Windows and Mac OS X simultaneously in April 2009, and the Linux version soon followed two months later in June of the same year.<ref name=\"Navicat SQLite notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQLite release notes|date=2010{{ndash}}14|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-sqlite-release-note}}</ref> In April 2010, Navicat Premium began including Navicat for SQLite starting from version 9 to expand the usability of Navicat Premium.<ref name=\"Navicat Premium notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Premium release notes|date=2009{{ndash}}14|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/products/navicat-premium-release-note}}</ref> Navicat for SQL Server was released in November 2010 for the Windows platform and Mac OS X. Also at the release, the SQL server version was included in the Premium version of Navicat. In January 2011, support for [[SQL Azure]] was added.<ref name=\"Navicat for SQL Server notes\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQL server overview|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-for-sqlserver}}</ref> Navicat for MariaDB was released in November 2013 for Windows, Mac OS X and Linux. Also at the release, the MariaDB version was included in both Navicat Premium and Navicat for MySQL.\n\nIn 2018, Navicat started to support NoSQL databases. [[MongoDB]] is currently the newest addition to the list of server Navicat supports. The new line of product, called Navicat for MongoDB, was released in July 2018 for Windows, Mac OS X and Linux. It provides a native environment for MongoDB management and supports the extra features like MapReduce, GridFS Buckets. Also at the release, the MongoDB version was included in Navicat Premium.\n\n===Navicat Premium===\nIn 2009, PremiumSoft released Navicat Premium, a series of Navicat software that combines all previous Navicat versions into a single version and can connect to different database types including MySQL, Oracle, and PostgreSQL simultaneously, allowing users to do data migration between cross databases. Navicat Premium version also supports cross-platform administration, serving Windows, Mac OS X and Linux. In April 2010, version 9 of Navicat Premium was released, which added the connectivity of SQLite database to Navicat Premium, allowing Navicat Premium to connect to MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL and SQLite in a single application. In November 2010, support for Microsoft SQL Server was added. In January 2011, [[SQL Azure]] was included. In November 2013, added the support of MariaDB.<ref name=\"Navicat Premium notes\"/><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Techmixer|title=Navicat Premium \u2013 Cross Database Administrator Management Tool|url=http://www.techmixer.com/navicat-premium-cross-database-administrator-management-tool}}</ref> In July 2018, added the support of MongoDB.\n\n===Navicat Essentials===\nNavicat Essentials was officially released in November 2011. This is a simple Navicat version for commercial use. The Essentials editions of Navicat lack several features found in the Standard/Enterprise editions, including form view, record filtering, visual query building, data modeling and options for import, export and backup of data, etc.<ref name=\"Navicat Essentials features\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Essentials features|url=https://navicat.com/en/products/navicat-essentials}}</ref>\n\n===Navicat Data Modeler===\nNavicat Data Modeler Windows version was officially released in March 2012. Then, Mac OS X and Linux version were released in May 2012 and June 2012. This is a standalone product for developers to create data models for MySQL, SQL Server, Oracle, PostgreSQL and SQLite databases. Navicat Data Modeler allows users to visually design database structures, perform reverse/forward engineer process, import table structures from ODBC data sources, generate SQL files and print models to files, etc. In June 2015, added the support of MariaDB databases and several features such as Model Conversion, Physical/Logical/Conceptual model types and Navicat Cloud.\n\n===Navicat iOS===\nIn August 2014, PremiumSoft released a new product - Navicat iOS.<ref name=\"Navicat iOS\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat iOS|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/products}}</ref> It is a database administration tool developed for iOS with features included object viewer & designer, query builder & editor, Navicat Cloud,<ref name=\"Navicat Cloud\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Cloud|url=https://www.navicat.com/en/navicat-cloud}}</ref> server monitor, etc. MySQL was supported in the first release. Then, Navicat for PostgreSQL iOS version was released in January 2015. In September 2017, Navicat for MariaDB iOS version was released.\n\n===Navicat Cloud Collaboration===\nNavicat Cloud is a cloud service for users to synchronize their connection settings, queries, models and virtual groups with multiple platforms and devices. A user can share his project to others for collaborating on connection settings, queries and models.\n\n===Navicat Monitor===\nNavicat Monitor was officially released in April 2018. It is a safe, simple and agentless remote server monitoring tool and supports to monitor MySQL, MariaDB and cloud databases. Users can access Navicat Monitor from anywhere via a web browser. The main features of Navicat Monitor including real-time instance performance monitoring, alert notification, query analyzer, replications monitoring.\n\n==Features==\nNavicat's features include:\n\n* code snippet\n* visual query-builder\n* SSH and [[HTTP tunneling]]<ref name=\"lasplash.com\"/>\n* data and structure migration and synchronization\n* import and export and backup of data\n* report builder\n* data modeling\n* task scheduling and wizards tool\n\nThere are differences in the features available across operating systems.<ref name=\"features_MySQL\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for MySQL Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-mysql-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_MariaDB\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for MariaDB Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-mariadb-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_PostegreSQL\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for PostegreSQL Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-postgresql-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_Oracle\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for Oracle Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-oracle-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_SQLite\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQLite Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-sqlite-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_SQLServer\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat for SQL Server Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-for-sqlserver-feature-matrix}}</ref><ref name=\"features_Premium\">{{cite web|accessdate=2014-12-01|publisher=Navicat|title=Navicat Premium Feature Matrix|url=https://www.navicat.com/products/navicat-premium-feature-matrix}}</ref>\n\nNavicat is also compatible with forks of [[MySQL]] such as [[Drizzle (database server)|Drizzle]], OurDelta, and Percona.<ref name=\"features_MySQL\"/>\n\nNavicat supports Cloud Databases like [[Amazon RDS]], [[Amazon Aurora]], [[Amazon Redshift]], [[SQL Azure]], [[Oracle Cloud]], [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]] and [[Alibaba Cloud]].<ref name=\"features_MySQL\"/><ref name=\"features_MariaDB\"/><ref name=\"features_PostegreSQL\"/><ref name=\"features_Oracle\"/><ref name=\"features_SQLServer\"/><ref name=\"features_Premium\"/>\n\n==Navicat Community==\nNavicat Community provides a flexible environment for Navicat users to post questions, share experiences and solutions. It includes forum discussions, blog articles, tutorial videos and Wiki FAQ.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Comparison of database tools]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.navicat.com/}}\n* [https://community.navicat.com/ Navicat Community]\n\n[[Category:MySQL]]\n[[Category:PostgreSQL]]\n[[Category:Database administration tools]]\n[[Category:Data modeling tools]]\n[[Category:Software companies of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Oracle database tools]]\n[[Category:Microsoft database software]]\n[[Category:MariaDB]]\n", "name_user": "Aliuwr", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update version", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navicat"}
{"title_page": "Bill Idelson", "text_new": "{{No footnotes|article|date=April 2009}}\n{{infobox person\n|image=Bill Idelson.jpg\n|caption=Idelson in 1937\n|birth_date={{birth date|mf=yes|1919|8|21}}\n|birth_place=[[Forest Park, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|mf=yes|2007|12|31|1919|8|21}}\n|death_place=Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n|occupation=Television, [[voice actor]], [[screenwriter]], [[Television producer|producer]]\n}}\n'''Bill Idelson''' (August 21, 1919 \u2013 December 31, 2007) was an actor, writer, director and producer widely known for his teenage role as Rush Gook on the radio comedy ''[[Vic and Sade]]'' and his recurring television role as [[The Dick Van Dyke Show#Characters|Herman Glimscher]] on ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'' in the 1960s.\n\n==Background==\nIdelson was born in [[Forest Park, Illinois]], his parents were Russian immigrants. He joined the U.S. Navy in [[World War II]] and was awarded a [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] and four [[Air Medal]]s as a night fighter pilot. He later married actress [[imdbname:2475409|Seemah Wilder]] with whom he had three sons, Paul, Howie and Jonathan<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite web\n  | title = Actor, writer on episodic TV got his start in radio\n  | newspaper = Los Angeles Times\n  | first = Bill\n  | last = McLellan\n  | date = January 6, 2008\n  | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2008/jan/06/local/me-idelson6}}</ref> as well as a daughter, TV writer and actress [[Ellen Idelson]], who died in 2003.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nIdelson died in 2007 from complications due to a hip injury.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/> On his death, writer-director [[Norman Corwin]] told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' Idelson was \"a luminary, he stood out among the radio comedians.\"<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/> Creator of the ''Dick Van Dyke Show'', [[Carl Reiner]], said Idelson was \"a very subtle actor. He made no big movements, and every time you cut to him you could get a laugh.\"<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Radio===\nIdelson's acting career began in 1931 on Chicago's [[WGN (AM)|WGN]] radio, when he played Skeezix on ''[[Gasoline Alley (radio)|Uncle Walt and Skeezix]]'', a radio drama based on the ''[[Gasoline Alley]]'' comic strip.<ref name=rs>DeLong, Thomas A. (1996). ''Radio Stars: An Illustrated Biographical Dictionary of 953 Performers, 1920 through 1960''. McFarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-2834-2}}. P. 136.</ref> One year later he landed the role of Rush on the long-running ''Vic and Sade'', playing the role until he joined the U.S. Navy.\n\nAfter the war, his acting credits included radio and television versions of the daytime drama series ''[[One Man's Family]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vernon|first1=Terry|title=Tele-Vues|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5556740/long_beach_independent/|work=Long Beach Independent|date=November 6, 1949|location=California, Long Beach|page=22|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 11, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nIn ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'' Idelson played Herman Glimscher, the [[Caspar Milquetoast|milquetoast]] boyfriend of Sally Rogers ([[Rose Marie]]). \"Herman could never marry because his mother wouldn't sign off on it yet, and when he had a date with Sally Rogers he brought his mother a couple of times,\" show creator and co-star [[Carl Reiner]] told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. He re-created the role in the first decade of the 21st Century for a reunion show of ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'', with Herman finally married to Sally as she joins her former colleague Rob Petrie (Van Dyke) to write a new special for their megalomaniacal former boss, Alan Brady (Reiner).\n\nIdelson guest starred on episodes of ''[[Dragnet (1951 TV series)|Dragnet]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'', ''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'', ''[[Happy Days]]'', ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' and ''[[Will & Grace]]'', in which he appeared along with his wife and daughter.\n\nHe wrote several episodes of ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'', leading him to further writing work on  ''The Twilight Zone'', ''[[Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.]]'', ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'', ''[[Get Smart]]'', ''The Odd Couple'', ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'' and ''Happy Days''. He received two Writers Guild Awards for best episodic comedy, one for an episode of ''Get Smart'' and the other for an episode of ''The Andy Griffith Show''.\n\nHis producing credits included ''[[The McLean Stevenson Show]]'', ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]'', ''[[Anna and the King]]'' and ''[[Love, American Style]]''.\n\n===Film===\nIdelson appeared as the head of a band organization in the film ''[[Pete Kelly's Blues (film)|Pete Kelly's Blues]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Bows in 'Blues'|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5561808/ames_daily_tribune/|work=Ames Daily Tribune|date=August 27, 1955|location=Iowa, Ames|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 12, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nHe was the author of three books, ''The Story of Vic and Sade'', ''Gibby'' (an autobiographical novel about a fighter pilot) and ''Bill Idelson's Writing Class''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0406857}}\n*[http://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/california/la-me-idelson6jan06,1,2585043.story?coll=la-headlines-pe-california \"Bill Idelson, 88; actor, writer, producer played the son on radio's 'Vic and Sade'.\"] McLellan, Dennis. (January 6, 2008). ''Los Angeles Times''.\n\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicComedyScreenplay 1960s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idelson, Bill}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male radio actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:People from Forest Park, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{No footnotes|article|date=April 2009}}\n{{infobox person\n|image=Bill Idelson.jpg\n|caption=Idelson in 1937\n|birth_date={{birth date|mf=yes|1919|8|21}}\n|birth_place=[[Forest Park, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|mf=yes|2007|12|31|1919|8|21}}\n|death_place=Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n|occupation=Television, [[voice actor]], [[screenwriter]], [[Television producer|producer]]\n}}\n'''Bill Idelson''' (August 21, 1919 \u2013 December 31, 2007) was an actor, writer, director and producer widely known for his teenage role as Rush Gook on the radio comedy ''[[Vic and Sade]]'' and his recurring television role as [[The Dick Van Dyke Show#Characters|Herman Glimscher]] on ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'' in the 1960s.\n\n==Background==\nIdelson was born in [[Forest Park, Illinois]], his parents were Russian immigrants. He joined the U.S. Navy in [[World War II]] and was awarded a [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] and four [[Air Medal]]s as a night fighter pilot. He later married actress [[imdbname:2475409|Seemah Wilder]] with whom he had three sons, Paul, Howie and Jonathan<ref name=\"latimesobit\">{{cite web\n  | title = Actor, writer on episodic TV got his start in radio\n  | newspaper = Los Angeles Times\n  | first = Bill\n  | last = McLellan\n  | date = January 6, 2008\n  | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2008/jan/06/local/me-idelson6}}</ref> as well as a daughter, TV writer and actress [[Ellen Idelson]], who died in 2003.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\nIdelson died in 2007 from complications due to a hip injury.<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/> On his death, writer-director [[Norman Corwin]] told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' Idelson was \"a luminary, he stood out among the radio comedians.\"<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/> Creator of the ''Dick Van Dyke Show'', [[Carl Reiner]], said Idelson was \"a very subtle actor. He made no big movements, and every time you cut to him you could get a laugh.\"<ref name=\"latimesobit\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Radio===\nIdelson's acting career began in 1931 on Chicago's [[WGN (AM)|WGN]] radio, when he played Skeezix on ''[[Gasoline Alley (radio)|Uncle Walt and Skeezix]]'', a radio drama based on the ''[[Gasoline Alley]]'' comic strip.<ref name=rs>DeLong, Thomas A. (1996). ''Radio Stars: An Illustrated Biographical Dictionary of 953 Performers, 1920 through 1960''. McFarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-2834-2}}. P. 136.</ref> One year later he landed the role of Rush on the long-running ''Vic and Sade'', playing the role until he joined the U.S. Navy.\n\nAfter the war, his acting credits included radio and television versions of the daytime drama series ''[[One Man's Family]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vernon|first1=Terry|title=Tele-Vues|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5556740/long_beach_independent/|work=Long Beach Independent|date=November 6, 1949|location=California, Long Beach|page=22|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 11, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nIn ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'' Idelson played Herman Glimscher, the [[Caspar Milquetoast|milquetoast]] boyfriend of Sally Rogers ([[Rose Marie]]). \"Herman could never marry because his mother wouldn't sign off on it yet, and when he had a date with Sally Rogers he brought his mother a couple of times,\" show creator and co-star [[Carl Reiner]] told the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. He re-created the role in the first decade of the 21st Century for a reunion show of ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'', with Herman finally married to Sally as she joins her former colleague Rob Petrie (Van Dyke) to write a new special for their megalomaniacal former boss, Alan Brady (Reiner).\n\nIdelson guest starred on episodes of ''[[Dragnet (1951 TV series)|Dragnet]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'', ''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'', ''[[Happy Days]]'', ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' and ''[[Will & Grace]]'', in which he appeared along with his wife and daughter.\n\nHe wrote several episodes of ''The Dick Van Dyke Show'', leading him to further writing work on  ''The Twilight Zone'', ''[[Gomer Pyle, U.S.M.C.]]'', ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'', ''[[Get Smart]]'', ''The Odd Couple'', ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'' and ''Happy Days''. He received two Writers Guild Awards for best episodic comedy, one for an episode of ''Get Smart'' and the other for an episode of ''The Andy Griffith Show''.\n\nHis producing credits included ''The McLean Stevenson Show'', ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]'', ''[[Anna and the King]]'' and ''[[Love, American Style]]''.\n\n===Film===\nIdelson appeared as the head of a band organization in the film ''[[Pete Kelly's Blues (film)|Pete Kelly's Blues]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Bows in 'Blues'|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5561808/ames_daily_tribune/|work=Ames Daily Tribune|date=August 27, 1955|location=Iowa, Ames|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 12, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nHe was the author of three books, ''The Story of Vic and Sade'', ''Gibby'' (an autobiographical novel about a fighter pilot) and ''Bill Idelson's Writing Class''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0406857}}\n*[http://www.latimes.com/news/printedition/california/la-me-idelson6jan06,1,2585043.story?coll=la-headlines-pe-california \"Bill Idelson, 88; actor, writer, producer played the son on radio's 'Vic and Sade'.\"] McLellan, Dennis. (January 6, 2008). ''Los Angeles Times''.\n\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicComedyScreenplay 1960s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idelson, Bill}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male radio actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:People from Forest Park, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Idelson"}
